<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, May 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will hold talks
with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Lisbon on Thursday instead of
Berlin as originally planned, Barak's office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Barak will meet Clinton in Lisbon early Thursday morning after
which he will return home to attend a state ceremony marking
Jerusalem Unification Day, said the office in a statement. (Israel-
US-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian State Duma on Wednesday overwhelmingly
approved a bill tabled by President Vladimir Putin on reforming
the country's upper house, the Federation Council.
</P>
<P>
The measure cleared the lower house of parliament by a vote of
362-34 with eight abstentions in the first reading, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Putin expressed "full satisfaction" with the approval. (Russia-
Parliament-Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria has fully accepted Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon, without demanding Israel pull out from the disputed
Shebaa Farms, said U.N. special envoy to the Middle East Terje
Roed-Larsen in Damascus on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said in a statement that Syria and the United Nations
agreed "on every matter" related to the pullout, which was hastily
completed last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Syria did not require the withdrawal include the Shebaa Farms,
the envoy told reporters after meeting with Syrian Foreign
Minister Faruk Shareh. (Syria-Israel-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and the United States have agreed to hold further talks at an
early date to continue discussing pending issues between the two
countries after concluding their talks in Rome, a spokesman for
the DPRK Foreign Ministry said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the vice-ministerial-level talks in Rome from May 24 to 30,
the two sides discussed the pending issue of lifting economic
sanctions against Pyongyang announced by Washington in 1999, the
spokesman said. (DPRK-US-Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian-Israeli final-status negotiations will
not be resumed on Wednesday as previously agreed, said Nabil Abu
Rdeineh, advisor to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio announced on Tuesday that the talks would be
resumed on Wednesday and would be moved from Stockholm to the
region.
</P>
<P>
Abu Rdeineh said the resumption of negotiations will be
discussed during a meeting of the Palestinian negotiating
committee to be held later in the day under the chairmanship of
Arafat. (Palestine-Israel-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Sri Lankan government said Wednesday its troops
had repelled an all-out offensive by Tamil Tiger rebels and seized
a cache of arms in the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said Tamil Tigers Tuesday had mounted an
attack at Chemmani, Colombuturai and Chavakachcheri, all in the
Jaffna peninsula but were repelled by the army, leaving seven
rebels dead. (S.Lanka-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Fiji's military leaders Wednesday dropped plans to
set up a civilian interim government and said it was possible the
army may run the country better, the Australian Associated Press (
AAP) said.
</P>
<P>
Just hours after naming a civilian to take over as interim
prime minister, military leaders suddenly withdrew the nomination
of former diplomat Ratu Epeli Nailatikau, the AAP said. (Australia-
Fiji)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- A plane carrying eight people is believed to have
crashed in Spencer Gulf in the South Australia state on Wednesday,
the Australian Maritime Safety Authority (AMSA) said.
</P>
<P>
Both engines on the Piper Chieftain aircraft failed while it
was flying from Adelaide to Whyalla about 7 p.m. (local time). (
Australia-Plane) 
</P>
</TEXT>
