<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration Workable for Arab Reconciliation: Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said on Thursday that the Damascus Declaration is a workable
formula for seeking reconciliation in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The declaration provides a "workable framework that could
greatly improve the inter-Arab relations" which have been in
trouble since Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait, Moussa told reporters
while commenting on an upcoming foreign ministers meeting of the
signatories.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting would review the items of the
declaration and its implementation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria and the six Gulf Cooperation Council states -
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates - signed the Damascus Declaration in March 1991 following
the Gulf War which ousted the Iraqi troops out of Kuwait. The
declaration called for cooperation in politics, economy and
regional security among the signatories.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the eight Arab countries will meet on
Monday and Tuesday in Cairo to discuss issues related to the Arab
world, especially the Middle East peace process and ways to restore
Arab solidarity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
