<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renowned Iranian War Veteran Killed in Road Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ali Akbar Abutorabi, a respected
Iranian war veteran during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war, was killed
Thursday in a traffic accident, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Abutorabi, a member of Iran's volunteer force Basij, and former
prisoner of war (POW) and parliament member, died with his father
when their car crashed into a truck trailer on the Nayshabour-
Sabzevar road in Iran's eastern Khorasan Province, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Upon hearing the news, President Mohammad Khatami expressed
condolence to supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and Abutorabi's
brother Mohammad Abutorabi, who is a member of the newly
inaugurated sixth Iranian Majlis (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Abutorabi was captured by Iraqi troops during the war and was
jailed in an Iraqi prisoners camp for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
After returning to Iran, he undertook the administration of the
POW affairs. He was a member of Iran's fourth and fifth Majlis
(1993-2001). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Greek City Discovered in Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A French-Egyptian archaeological
mission has discovered an ancient city dating back to the Greek era
in the water near Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency reported on Thursday that led by
French adventurer Franc Godeo, the mission found the lost city of
Herculum six meters deep in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The location was four kilometers off the Abu Qir Bay to the
northeast of Alexandria, the news agency said, without giving the
date of the discovery.
</P>
<P>
Herculum is the second Greek city found in the sea near
Alexandria. The first was the city of Menotus discovered in 1934.
</P>
<P>
Six cities built in the ancient Greek era around 320 BC sank
into the sea off the northern coast of Egypt when a major
earthquake rocked the area in the ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of Herculum helped unravel a mystery about Abu
Qir, which was originally known as Canub dedicated to the worship
of God Osiris, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, the mission found more than 100
statues in various sizes and shapes belonging to the Greek,
Ptolemaic (305 BC to 30 BC) and Roman (30 BC to 395 AD) eras, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Denies Final-Status Negotiations Have Resumed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said
on Thursday afternoon that the final-status negotiations between
Palestinians and Israelis had not resumed.
</P>
<P>
Arafat confirmed that there was an Israeli invitation, but no
decision has been made by the Palestinian side on the matter.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian negotiating committee is still discussing the
subject," Arafat told reporters after he presided over an emergency
meeting of the Palestinian National Council to welcome Najma
Heptulla, president of the council of the Inter-Parliamentary
Union.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports quoted an unidentified senior Israeli official
as saying that the talks for working out a comprehensive peace deal
with the Palestinians by September would resume in Israel Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak flew to Lisbon, Portugal
Thursday to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton on the Middle East
issues. He was reportedly accusing Arafat of "foot-dragging" during
the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
