<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy, Lebanese President Meet Over Border Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Middle East Envoy Roed Larsen
Thursday held talks with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Prime
Minister Salim Hoss on the Israeli-Lebanese border division.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Larsen told reporters the two sides aired their
views on the border issue and decided to dispatch experts to
conduct an on-the-spot survey later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the U.N. and Lebanon will hold a meeting on the issue
on the basis of the results of the survey, the National News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon accused the U.N. of being biased toward Israel in
verifying Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon, saying Israeli
troops still remains in 16 areas that belong to Lebanon, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Larsen is holding shuttle talks among Israel, Lebanon and Syria
on verifying Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has refused repeatedly to deploy troops
in south Lebanon after the Israeli pullout on May 24 from the
region, where the resistance group Hezbollah and Amal movement are
in control of the former occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss stressed Wednesday the
Lebanese army will not be deployed in the south until the U.N.
confirms Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
