<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen's Foreign Exchange Reserve Hits 2 Billion U. S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The foreign exchange reserve at the
Central Bank of Yemen (CBY) has exceeded two billion U.S. dollars,
the highest level in the history of the Yemeni economy.
</P>
<P>
The rise is attributed to the economic, fiscal and monetary
reforms adopted by the Yemeni government since 1995 under a request
from the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the
Yemeni News Agency (YNA) reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reserve represents a 33 percent increase since early this
year, thus placing the national economy on a secure position.
</P>
<P>
YNA also attributed the increase to the improvement of oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
Yemen's income from oil exports, the main source of foreign
exchange in the country, went up from 1.4 billion U.S. dollars last
year to 1.8 billion U.S. dollars early May and exceeded two billion
at present.
</P>
<P>
Oil products account for 95 percent of Yemen's exports and their
value hit 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Yemen started exporting oil in 1988 when its total revenues
stood at 397 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
