<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Needs Strong Energy Market, Says Greek Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Greek Development Minister Nikos
Christodoulakis said here Thursday that Europe needed a strong
energy market that would respect the environment.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a two-day European energy conference, which began
Thursday, Christodoulakis said that creating a European energy
market needed a regulatory framework to regulate private and state
behavior and motives to implement the necessary energy
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
As for the efforts made by Greece to liberalize its energy
market, he described the forthcoming floatation of the state-run
Public Power Corporation (PPC), the completion of a tender to
supply household electricity in northern Greece and the creation
of an energy futures market as important steps.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that an agreement between Greece and
Turkey to draft a feasibility study on new energy transport routes
from the Caspian Sea to Europe and a Greek-Italian cooperation in
the energy sector were of great importance.
</P>
<P>
The energy conference, which was organized by the European
Union (EU) and Greece's Development Ministry, aims to promote
cooperation  between the EU, the Black Sea and Mediterranean
countries in major energy issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
