<HEADLINE> Police Storms Day-Care Center to Save Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Police Thursday launched an armed
assault on the day-care center where an armed man had held more
than two dozens of children hostage for 28 hours.
</P>
<P>
Local television reports said that police forces stormed the
nursery school at Wasserbillig near the Luxembourg-Germany border
and the hostage taker was reportedly shot by a police sniper.
</P>
<P>
But there was no report on any casualty on the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Police believed that the 39-year-old man, armed with a pistol,
a hand grenade and a knife, held 25 children and three female
adults hostage in the nursery school from Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, the man, who had been demanding to be
flown out to Libya with around 20 million francs (220,000 U.S.
dollars released four children including one aged just over two.
</P>
<P>
The youngest child held captive was believed to be only 22
months old.
</P>
<P>
The police from both Luxembourg and Germany launched an armed
assault though Luxembourg Interior Minister Michel Wolter
instructed earlier that no violence should occur in the solution
of the hostage taking crisis.
</P>
<P>
The gunman was said to be from Tunisia originally and settled
down in Luxembourg in 1982 and had a history of mental problems.
</P>
<P>
He had released 10 children late on Wednesday after he was
allowed to speak to his psychiatrist. 
</P>
