<HEADLINE> Mozambican Group Denies Press Claim on Obsolete Pesticide Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican environmental group,
Livaningo, has denied a claim in a Maputo newspaper "Correio de
Manha" that it wanted to export the obsolete pesticides currently
stored in Matola to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
A Livaningo press release said on Thursday that Livaningo had
never been involved in any discussions on this matter, and had
merely suggested to the Environment Ministry some possible
destinations for the pesticides.
</P>
<P>
These destinations were Holland, Britain and Denmark -- all
European countries with the facilities for destroying such toxic
waste safely.
</P>
<P>
Livaningo, based in Matola, 10 kilometers from Maputo,
suggested that the story in "Correio de Manha" had been planted by
somebody in the government in order to discredit the environmental
group, which is opposed to the government's plan to incinerate
some of 850 tons waste pesticides in the furnaces of the Matola
cement factory.
</P>
<P>
Livaningo had no difficulty in proving that it never advocated
dumping Mozambique's obsolete pesticides in the lap of South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Livaningo argued that last month's report from a Danish mission
review team showed that Livaningo's concerns are legitimate.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, which funds the pesticide disposal project, is
beginning to lose their initial enthusiasm for incineration, and
the May report suggested that two "experimental incinerations"
would be needed before giving the green light to burning hundreds
of tons of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Those experiments are needed to indicate whether incineration
releases into the atmosphere dangerous levels of poisons, and to
prove that at least 99.9 percent of the pesticides are in fact
destroyed by the furnace.
</P>
<P>
"After analyzing this document, we are more convinced than ever
that our reservations and doubts about undertaking any kind of
incineration safely in the cement factory are well grounded,"
declared Livaningo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
