<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Welcomes S. Africa's Support for Land Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
has welcomed efforts by his South African counterpart Thabo Mbeki
to raise funds for Zimbabwe's land reform program.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told the Zimbabwe News Agency on Thursday that South
Africa's initiative, which has so far yielded about 15 million
U.S. dollars from donors, would reinvigorate the country's program
to redistribute white- owned farmland to thousands of landless
blacks.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome their independent effort to secure funding for our
land reform program. The funds are useful to us in reinforcing
our efforts to resettle our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has reportedly persuaded Saudi Arabia and some Nordic
countries to put up 15 million U.S. dollars to buy white-owned
farms in Zimbabwe for redistribution to blacks.
</P>
<P>
"We have not got any message from them but we are aware of
their efforts, " Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
According to Director-General in Mbeki's office Frank Chikane,
the Zimbabwean government would use the money to buy 118 farms
from white owners who were willing to sell their land.
</P>
<P>
The land issue has in the last few months come to the fore in
the southern African nation of 12.5 million people as war veterans
of the 1970s liberation struggle occupied more than 1,000
white-owned commercial farms to demand speedy land redistribution.
</P>
<P>
This had led to an international outcry as clashes between the
war veterans and white farmers resulted in deaths and damage of
property worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Zimbabwe's former colonial master, has promised to
provide fund for the resettlement program on condition that the
farm invasion must end first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
