<HEADLINE> S. African Anti-Corruption Unit Calls for Political Will </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- South African Special
Investigating Unit on Thursday called for a stronger political
will to combat corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
Willem Heath, head of the unit, told in Midrand near
Johannesburg that potential investors would be encouraged by a
clear policy that government was serious about tackling
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"(But) South Africa has not accepted this unconditionally and
the political will is questionable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Heath said many politicians and senior civil servants in third
world countries regarded the appointment of a permanent,
independent, anti- corruption agency as a bad reflection on the
government, but the opposite was also true.
</P>
<P>
"If... the perception is created that the government is doing
all in its power to address the problem, this is a clear
invitation to investors and possible developers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Heath said his unit was also hampered by delays in the
publication of proclamations required for an investigation to go
ahead.
</P>
<P>
"In many of these cases the unit could have avoided the loss
of state assets and money through urgent interdicts, attachment
orders or the freezing of bank accounts," Heath said.
</P>
<P>
He said corruption ultimately led to a loss of money, and a
lack of trust by potential investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
