<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Radio Presenter Sentenced to 12 Years in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) Thursday sentenced Georges Ruggiu to 12
years in jail for his role in the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the 45-minute judgement before a packed courtroom in
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha where the U.N. tribunal is
based, Presiding Judge Navanathem Pillay said the sentence goes
into force immediately though the convict will be transferred to
another designated country to serve his sentence, from which the
three years Ruggiu has spent in detention awaiting trial will be
deducted.
</P>
<P>
Judge Pillay accused Ruggiu, former journalist and presenter
for Rwandan Radio Television Libre des Mille Collines (RTLM), of
inciting the genocide through his broadcasts in French. At least
half a million minority ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus were
killed in Rwanda during the 100-day massacre.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiu, a Belgium-born Italian, changed his plea on May 15 this
year from not guilty to guilty to two counts of direct and public
incitement to genocide and persecution.
</P>
<P>
Arrested on July 23, 1997, in Mombasa, Kenya, the 42-year-old
convict is the only non-Rwandan detained by the ICTR.
</P>
<P>
The defense lawyers, Mohamed Aouini from Tunisia and Jean-Louis
Gilissen from Belgium, said they expected nothing better than what
was handed to Ruggiu.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the independent Hirondelle News Agency,
Rwanda has criticized the 12-year prison sentence handed down on
Ruggiu as being too lenient.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Rwanda's representative to the ICTR Martin Ngoga as
saying that it has ignored the gravity of the crimes of which he
has been convicted, and to which he pleaded guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
