<HEADLINE> Georgian Defense Minister's Brother Killed in Car Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Guram Tevzadze, brother of the
Georgian defense minister David Tevzadze and the head of the
Foundation for Support to the Georgian Army, was killed in a car
explosion Thursday noon, reported Russian media.
</P>
<P>
The blast occurred when Tevzadze was driving a car out of the
capital of Tbilis, said the Georgian Interior Ministry press
center, brand the incident as a "terrorist act."
</P>
<P>
Tevzadze's wife and a male relative, who were also in the car,
were injured and taken to hospital.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian police have confirmed that the explosion is a
terrorist act. The detective have found TNT traces inside the car.
</P>
<P>
It was a remote control bomb, which was laid under the bottom
of the car in the area of the driver's seat, and the perpetrators
were following behind Guram Tevzadze's car, said the police.
</P>
<P>
Tevzadze, the head of the "Georgian Intellect" public
organization for support to the army, was a successful businessman.
The organization founded by Grigory Kinteraya, an ethnic-Georgian
businessman living in Germany, was a trade agent and supplied
foodstuffs to the army.
</P>
<P>
A scandal surrounding the organization occurred in early 1999
when the organization chiefs were accused of financial
machinations,including the use of up to 5 million lari (2.5
million U.S. dollars)from the budget in shady dealings. 
</P>
