<HEADLINE> Wing Hang and Dah Sing Banks Individual Ratings Upgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the same time, both banks' Long-term, Short-term and Support
ratings are affirmed at 'A-', 'F2' and '4' respectively, according
to an announcement by the Agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fitch IBCA said Hongkong's banks, in general, fared
surprisingly well during the Asian economic crisis of 1997-1999.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to their prudent management, sound capital base and
strong liquidity, Hongkong's financial institutions have remained
generally solid throughout the financial turmoil, it added.
</P>
<P>
In line with its peers, Wing Hang Bank was affected by the
economic depression in Hongkong in 1997-1999, causing its ROE fell
to below its historical norm, which, it should be noted, had been
better than the banking system average, the Agency argued.
</P>
<P>
As Hongkong economy has begun to recover since the second half
of 1999, Wing Hang's performance has also started to improve.
</P>
<P>
Fitch IBCA said, since June 1999, the bank's impaired loans,
including non-accrual loans, overdue loans and rescheduled loans,
show a similar, falling trend.
</P>
<P>
Having experienced a setback in 1998, when profitability
declined and non-accrual loans surged, Dah Sing Bank's performance
rebounded remarkably in 1999 as ROE, ROA and net profit doubled.
</P>
<P>
The Agency said, following the bottoming out of non-accrual
loans, a substantial increase in loan loss provisions in 2000 is
not expected. Therefore, the bank's profitability should remain
healthy and its financial profile sound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
