<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Visit Middle East Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright is scheduled to arrive in the region on Monday in an
effort to "narrow the gap" between Israel and the Palestinians in
final-status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The visit was announced by United States President Bill Clinton
Thursday in Lisbon, Portugal after his meeting there with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak, flew to Lisbon especially for the meeting with Clinton,
will rush back to Israel later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio quoted U.S. embassy officials in Israel as saying
that Albright will hold separate talks with Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. top diplomat will return to Washington Tuesday evening
or Wednesday after the meetings, the embassy officials added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian negotiations have entered a crucial
stage and Clinton has decided to send Albright to the region to
push forward the talks, they added.
</P>
<P>
During the last two rounds of secret talks last month in
Stockholm, Sweden, progress was made on hammering out a framework
agreement on final-status issues, said Israeli Public Security
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, who headed the Israeli delegation at the
talks.
</P>
<P>
But the back-channel talks were called off by Barak on May 21
due to an upsurge of violent anti-Israel demonstrations in the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
An official accompanying Barak to the Lisbon summit said
Thursday the secret talks would resume Thursday night in Israel,
but Arafat said there was no decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
There have been two tracks of final-status talks. One was
attended by Israeli chief negotiator Oded Eran and his Palestinian
counterpart Yasser Abed Rabbo, while the other one was held between
Ben-Ami and Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qurei.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has urged Clinton to put more pressure on Israel to force
it to make compromise in the final-status talks, which deal with
such thorny issues as Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, Jewish
settlements, border, security and water.
</P>
<P>
Barak blamed the Palestinian side for "foot-dragging" in
negotiations aimed to nail down a frame-work agreement and pave the
way for the signing of a permanent peace treaty by September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
