<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Drops in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. construction spending
dropped 0.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 757.3
billion U.S. dollars in April, the first decline in seven months,
the Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 0.6 percent decline followed strong gains of 0.8 percent in
March, 1.3 percent in February and 2 percent in January. It was
the first decline since a tiny 0.03 percent drop in September and
the biggest drop since 0.9 percent in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
The construction report was the latest indication that the U.S.
economy may finally be slowing under the weight of six interest
rate increases engineered by the Federal Reserve over the past
year in an effort to slow growth and keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the Labor Department said the number of
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits rose a
modest 1,000 last week but remained at a level indicating an
extremely tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
The weakness in construction sector was led by a 1.1 percent
fall in residential construction, which declined to an annual rate
of 340.1 billion dollars with both single-family homes and
apartment complexes showing decreases.
</P>
<P>
Spending on government building projects was down 0.6 percent
to an annual rate of 173.4 billion dollars as outlays for school
buildings, highways and military facilities dropped.
</P>
<P>
Bucking the downward trend, spending by the private sector on
office buildings and other commercial structures actually rose
during April by 1 percent to an annual rate of 203.4 billion
dollars. Increases were registered in office buildings, hotels and
hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
