<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Denies Final-Status Negotiations Have Resumed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said
on Thursday afternoon that the final-status negotiations between
Palestinians and Israelis had not resumed.
</P>
<P>
Arafat confirmed that there was an Israeli invitation, but no
decision has been made by the Palestinian side on the matter.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian negotiating committee is still discussing the
subject," Arafat told reporters after he presided over an emergency
meeting of the Palestinian National Council to welcome Najma
Heptulla, president of the council of the Inter-Parliamentary
Union.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports quoted an unidentified senior Israeli official
as saying that the talks for working out a comprehensive peace deal
with the Palestinians by September would resume in Israel Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak flied to Lisbon, Portugal
Thursday to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton on the Middle East
issues. He was reportedly accusing Arafat of "foot-dragging" during
the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
