<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 41,000 Eritreans Cross Border to Sudan: UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) announced Thursday that it had
registered around 41,000 Eritrean asylum seekers who had arrived
in Sudan's eastern state of Kassaia over the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR office in Kenya's capital Nairobi said that the
influx continues but at a lower rate over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Most of the recent arrivals coming from the Mohammed Ali Hassan
farm were able to pay the equivalent of 100 to 300 U.S. dollars to
rent trucks to transport them to Sudan, the U.N. agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency is concerned about the plight of many of the 50,000
displaced people reportedly gathered at the farm who can not
afford to pay passage to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR said that it is airlifting urgently needed relief
supplies to Sudan and an Airbus 300 is scheduled to arrive in
Khartoum Thursday, bringing in 42 tons of plastic sheeting,
kitchen sets and medical kits from Copenhagen and Cairo.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR office here also said that the agency has so far
delivered more than 2,400 tents to the Sudanese Commission on
Refugees for distribution to the new arrivals, in addition to
blankets, kitchen sets, soaps and high protein biscuits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Calls for Self-reliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said here on Thursday that Kenya cannot rely on outsiders to solve
many problems the east African country is facing.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, poverty and lack of self-sufficiency in food
call for hard work, commitment and innovativeness on the part of
our farmers," he told thousands of people at the celebrations of
the Madaraka Day to mark Kenya's self-rule from Britain 37 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, poverty, unemployment, poor
performance of agriculture, high cost of food, education, health
and transport are some of the major problems facing Kenya in the
new century.
</P>
<P>
Moi urged Kenyan farmers to respond more aggressively to the
challenge of food self-sufficiency despite the current erratic
weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Our farmers must redouble their efforts in order to expand
areas for food crops and produce more milk, meat, vegetables and
fruits to satisfy both our domestic and export requirements, now
and in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "we cannot claim to be in full control over
our affairs when we cannot feed ourselves; we cannot win the
respect of other nations when we continue to rely on handouts from
outsiders."
</P>
<P>
Kenya has fulfilled many conditions for the resumption of the
loans from the donor countries and international financial
institutions, Moi said, adding that Kenya hopes to start receiving
donor support very soon.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated his determination to continue the ongoing
privatization process, fight against corruption and improve
security in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
