<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-business Adoption Among HK SMEs Shows Slight Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- E-business among Small and Medium
Enterprises (SMEs) of Hong Kong has slightly advanced in the first
quater of this year, according to the result of a survey released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly survey, jointly conducted by the Hong Kong
Productivity Council (HKPC) and IBM China/Hong Kong Limited, shows
that 58 percent of the respondents with a webpage are aware of the
categories of their visitor, an increase of 10 percentage points
compared with that of last quarter.
</P>
<P>
On the effectiveness of the webpage as a marketing tool, 51
percent of the companies with an on-line product catalogue
expressed that the webpage can help business transactions, an
increase of seven percentage points from the last survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey was launched in September, 1999, to study and
monitor the development and adoption of e-business in Hong Kong
and provide the local business sector with a useful reference for
formulating business strategies accordingly.
</P>
<P>
In the survey, the deployment of e-business was classified into
six levels ranging from level 0 to 5, representing No Intention,
Show Intention, Basic Adoption, Prospecting, Business Integration
and Business Transformation respectively.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,063 local companies were interviewed by phone for
the third survey conducted in April 2000 and the result has been
grossed up to the whole population of around 207,274 active
establishments in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In terms of basic adoption, the survey shows that for 28.5
percent of the establishments, e-business usage is confined to E-
mail communications only.
</P>
<P>
At the level 3 of Prospecting, 8.7 percent of the companies
has a webpage and E-mail account, compared with 6.7 percent in the
last survey, an indication that more SMEs are now willing to
further enhance their e-business capabilities.
</P>
<P>
At level 4 and level 5, the indexes remained little unchanged
over the last quarter, an indication that web applications for
either on-line transaction or business integration of external or
internal information technology systems are still not commonly
used among local SMEs.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the survey findings, Wendy Wong, senior
consultant of HKPC, said "although the survey reflects an upward
tendency of e-business adoption in Hong Kong, the growth is at a
relatively slow pace."
</P>
<P>
"HKPC will continue to launch new initiatives to promote a
wider adoption of e-business by SMEs," she said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Ngai, executive of general business of IBM, said "the
level 4 and 5 indexes have remain unchanged for the last two
surveys, an indication that there could be a barrier for companies
in level 2 and 3 to advance further in deploying e-business. This
is most likely related to the security issue, which, as validated
by our own research, is a key concern for most companies."
</P>
<P>
"IBM is committed to helping local SMEs foster the e-business
adoption process by providing them with secured and cost-effective
solutions that cater for their need," Ngai added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
