<HEADLINE> Border Oil Trade Limits Frustrate Turkey's Southeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Civilian and military officials in
southeastern Turkey urged Ankara to open new border gates with Iraq
to prevent oil smuggling which would benefit the outlawed Kurdistan
Workers Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Local authorities were dismayed by a recent government decision
to restrict border oil trade with Iraq, which was allegedly aimed
to prevent the fuel money from flowing into the PKK that has been
involved in armed struggle since 1984 for an independent state in
the Kurdish-populated southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Local officials claimed the move will further hurt the ailing
economy of the region, where trade is the major source of income,
and encourage smuggling that will only benefit Kurdish separatist
militants, Turkish Daily News reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The governors in southeastern Turkey complained that the Ankara
authorities did not consult them before making such decisions.
</P>
<P>
Military sources in the southeast said they had sent reports to
Ankara, calling for opening up at least two new border gates with
the Kurdish-populated northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Iraqi Kurds have been cooperating with
the Turkish military in fighting PKK separatists who are trying to
find a foothold in northern Iraq after being uprooted in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
But the Iraqi Kurds rely on income from Iraq's fuel trade with
Turkey. Thus, any restrictions on border trade will hurt their
revenues and negatively affect Turkey's ability to influence them.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Husamettin Ozkan has reportedly
promised to correct the mistakes and revitalize the border trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
