<HEADLINE> Philippine Exports Up 10.6 Percent in 1st Four  Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine exports grew by 10.6
percent in the first four months this year to 11.27 billion U.S.
dollars from 10.19 billion dollars a year earlier, the government
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
For the month of April alone, total receipts increased by 13.7
percent to 2.66 billion dollars from 2.34 billion dollars last
year, said the National Statistics Office (NSO) in a press release.
</P>
<P>
While accounting for 47.4 percent of the aggregate April 2000
revenue, exports of the electronics and components went down by 4.
2 percent to 1.26 billion dollars in April from 1.32 billion
dollars last year, the NSO said.
</P>
<P>
Input/output/Peripheral Units remained as the second top earner,
with an export value of 243.91 million dollars or 74.3 percent
higher than 139.93 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The third top earner for the month consisted of Articles of
Appeal and Clothing Accessories with sales amounting to 170.32
million dollars, which was a 28 percent increase from 133.03
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government agency said that the exports to the
United States, accounting for 28.7 percent of the aggregate
receipt for the month, valued at 766.74 million dollars and inched
up by 5.7 percent from 725.54 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Japan followed with a 16.5 percent share. Valued at 439.09
million dollars, exports to Japan increase by 34.1 percent from
327.53 percent million dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
