<HEADLINE> Manila Clarifies Forthcoming Visit of OIC Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC)
Secretary General Azzedine Laraki will visit the Philippines in a
bid to secure an early release of the hostages in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Foreign Affairs (DFA) said in a statement
that Laraki will come to Manila to express both the OIC's concern
for the safety of the hostages as well as its support for the
efforts of the Philippine government to secure the release of the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the release of the hostages is the
responsibility of the Philippine Government alone, the DFA added.
</P>
<P>
The OIC head is expected to reiterate the OIC's call for the
government to continue to exert its utmost in order to arrive at a
peaceful solution to the humanitarian crisis that would ensure the
release of the hostages and their return to their countries as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The DFA explained that Laraki's visit to Manila will be similar
in nature to that of European Union (EU) envoy Javier Solana, who
paid a visit to Manila in a bid to secure an early safe release of
the Sulu hostages abducted by the Abu Sayyaf extremists from
Malaysia in April.
</P>
<P>
It said the EU's mission was aimed at manifesting the EU's
solidarity with the kidnap victims as well as with the Philippine
government's endeavor to secure their release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
