<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gunman Identified Otherwise in Luxembourg Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The gunman holding more than two
dozens of children and three adults hostage for more than 21 hours
since Wednesday was originally from Tunisia and not from Algeria,
police sources said.
</P>
<P>
The 39-year-old man, armed with a pistol, a hand grenade and a
knife, took as hostage 29 children aged between two and seven and
three female teachers from the Wasserbillig nursery school on
Wednesday afternoon, according to Belgian media reports.
</P>
<P>
He has been demanding to be flown to Libya with around 20
million francs (220,000 U.S. dollars) in return for the release of
the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Though the deadline he set for being escorted to a nearby
airport and flown out to Libya was well passed, no incident
happened, to the relief of parents, relatives, police and rescue
workers at the scene.
</P>
<P>
The deadline was set for 8.30 a.m. (0630 GMT) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The gunman, who has a history of mental problems, has allowed
two children to walk out of the school building early on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He released more than a dozen children late Wednesday after he
was allowed to speak to his psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg Foreign Minister Lydie Polfer visited Wasserbillig
together with Portuguese and French officials.
</P>
<P>
Besides Luxembourg children, the hostages include Portuguese
and French kids.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg Interior Minister Michel Wolter on Wednesday
instructed that the hostage taking incident be ended without
violence though the police had cordoned off the school building
and had their guns trained on the windows of the building in the
village of Wasserbillig near the Luxembourg-Germany border.
</P>
</TEXT>
