<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton tried Wednesday to reassure
European allies on a proposed U.S. missile defense program, saying
Washington would share the technology with friendly, "civilized"
countries if it decides to build such a system.
</P>
<P>
-- Lucent Technologies Inc. bought Chromatis Networks Inc., a
small Herndon company that has never sold a single product but
stands at the intersection of the newest Internet gold rush.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- A United Nations envoy said Syria was ready to accept that
Israel had completely withdrawn from southern Lebanon. Such a
decision could lessen chances of renewed violence on the Israel-
Lebanon border.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Vice President Al Gore called for legislation requiring
health insurers to provide children with mental health benefits
comparable to coverage for physical ailments.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Microsoft asked for major changes to the government's
proposal to break it into two companies. Lawyers for Microsoft
said they still don't believe such a remedy would be sustained by
an appeals court. The company said a breakup and sweeping
restrictions on its conduct would have damaging unintended
consequences.
</P>
<P>
-- New-homes sales dropped an unexpectedly hard 5.8 percent to
an annual rate of 909,000 in April, its lowest point since
November. The leading-indicator index slipped 0.1 percent, as
manufacturers' orders for consumer goods declined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
