<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Critical of EU's View on Defense Identity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
on Thursday described the views held by Turkey and the European
Union(EU) regarding the European Security and Defense Identity
(ESDI) as "rather contradictory," reported the Anatolia News Agency
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While meeting Javier Solana, EU Common Foreign and Security
Policy Commissioner and Western European Union (WEU) Secretary-
General, here on Thursday morning, Cem expressed hope that the two
sides would reach a compromise in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been eager to involve itself in the ESDI process ever
since it was accepted to be candidate for membership of the 15-
member European club at the Helsinki summit last december. But EU
appears reluctant to include non-EU NATO nations in the European
defense structure.
</P>
<P>
Solana arrived in Ankara Wednesday night for a one-day visit to
Turkey and will have a series of high-level contacts in Ankara. He
is expected to meet President Ahmet Necdet Sezer later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had looked forward to bringing its concern over the ESDI
issue to the agenda of its meeting with Solana.
</P>
<P>
Cem said that Solana had provided great support to Turkey on the
eve of the Helsinki summit, and expressed belief that they would
continue to work in a productive manner as they did in the past.
</P>
<P>
Noting that they had made an evaluation of Turkey's relations
with the European Union and NATO, Cem said that "There exists a
great difference between the opinions of Turkey and those of the EU
regarding the ESDI. But I believe that we will come up with a
compromise that would be satisfactory for both sides."
</P>
<P>
Solana said in his part that he and Cem would make an assessment
of the Turkey-EU relations in the post-Helsinki period.
</P>
<P>
The non-EU NATO allies, namely Turkey, Norway, Poland, Hungary,
and the Czech Republic, want to take part in the decision-making
mechanism of the ESDI. Their overtures have received support from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the issue reflects a striking difference
between the EU and the United States over the establishment of an
independent European defense system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
