<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summer Fishing Ban in South China Sea Enforced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China began to impose fishing bans
in South China Sea from 12:00 hours Beijing Time today. By 15:00
hours, no fishing ships were found to have violated the ban.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Fishery Bureau under the Ministry of
Agriculture said that the number of fishing ships participating in
the ban increased by more than 50 percent over last year to 26,853
due to the ban being imposed on more types of fishing ships.
</P>
<P>
He said that 296 fishery management ships were sent today to
cruise and inspect fishing waters north of 12 degrees north
latitude and have found no ships that violated the ban.
</P>
<P>
China began summer fishing bans in the East China Sea and
Yellow Sea from 1995 to protect dwindling marine fishing resources.
Last year, the ban was expanded to South China Sea. Statistics
indicate that within two months after the fishing ban was imposed,
the fishing output in these areas grew from 10 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the success of the ban, leading groups on fishing ban
have been set up in Guangdong and Hainan provinces as well as
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. Local fishery departments will
send out all fishery management ships and aircraft to patrol the
area. Fishing ships found to violate the ban will be severely
punished, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
