<HEADLINE> BP Amoco's China Venture Profitable in First-Year Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The world third largest
petrochemical company BP Amoco has made three million U.S. dollars
of profits with its joint venture in China in its first year of
operation, a senior company official said here today.
</P>
<P>
David A. Henley, vice president of BP Amoco China and chairman
of the joint venture, said that the company will increase
investment in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks at a press conference about the Chongqing-
Western China Development International Seminar to be held here
next week.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, Yangtze River Acetyls Co., Ltd., began
operations in Chongqing in southwest China in November 1998. It
reached a production capacity of 150,000 tons of acetic acid in
1999. It has raised production capacity to 200,000 tons every year
and occupies 30 percent of the acetic acid market in China. It
will increase its annual capacity to 350,000 tons by the first
quarter of 2003.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will also start to produce ethyl acetate and
butyl acetate in 2002. 
