<HEADLINE> HK Securities Markets Urged to Offer Quality Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's securities markets
were urged to use technology to offer quality services at
competitive prices, according to a senior SFC official.
</P>
<P>
The need for rapid development of technology in Hong Kong's
financial markets within an appropriate regulatory framework is
the key theme of the Securities and Futures Commission's (SFC)
11th annual report published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his chairman's statement of the report, SFC Chairman Andrew
L T Sheng said that technology has changed securities markets
profoundly in character, depth and liquidity, and "our financial
technology must be ready for connection with the rest of the world.
"
</P>
<P>
The challenges presented by rapid advances in technology and
sweeping market reforms and the need to contain costs were
successfully met during the year under review, Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the future SFC's work, the SFC chairman said the
key tasks to be tackled include the development of on-line trading
and electronic initial public offerings and guidelines for the
approval of automated trading systems.
</P>
<P>
Also included are an upgrading of clearing arrangements to
include scripless trading and straight-through processing for
securities and futures markets and the creation of an electronic
investor resources center to aid investor education.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, Sheng said that the SFC must prepare and upgrade
for the new economy. The commission is applying technology to
improve efficiency, introducing a more orderly workflow and
allowing the provision of online information management and
information sharing within the commission.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for online trading in Hong Kong have begun, and
the automated trading system of the Hong Kong Futures Exchange was
under extensive industry-wide test last year, according to Sheng.
</P>
<P>
The technology, media and telecommunications sector of the
stock market grew to 42 percent of the total as supply grew to
meet strong investor demand. Interest was further stimulated by
the launch of the Growth Enterprise Market, where 61 percent of
the companies listed had high technology content, indicating the
new economy began to grip Hong Kong and bring both challenges and
advances, Sheng concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
