<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Develops Environment Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The government of Bangladesh in
collaboration with the World Bank and The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) has undertaken a two-year program to
develop environmental management guidelines in the country, The
Financial Express reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sustainable Environment Management Program of the
Ministry of Environment and Forest, the World Bank engaged
Environmental Services of Australia and Survey Research Group of
Bangladesh to undertake the development of sectoral guidelines for
environmental management.
</P>
<P>
Project officials said one of the purposes of the guidelines is
to provide technical information and recommendations to guide,
promote and facilitate improved environmental performance by the
relevant sectors.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines will also strengthen the environmental
management capacity of government agencies and provide a sound
technical basis for assessing proposals and applications,
determining technical requirements, making statutory decisions,
and monitoring and regulating sector performance.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines would be produced in four batches, each over a
period of about five months.
</P>
<P>
The program will cover 18 industrial sectors, including oil and
gas exploration, power generation, shrimp farming and processing,
hospital and clinic waste management, leather tanning, garment
manufacturing,etc.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines should be relevant and practicable for the
sectors and promote action and encourage progress by the sectors
toward cost-effective practice in environmental management in the
Bangladesh context, environment experts said.
</P>
<P>
World Bank's Country Director Frederick Temple said Bangladesh
is still facing the challenge of poverty alleviation, reminding
that there is a link between poverty and environment.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the crucial relationship between poverty and
environment should be taken into consideration by the policy-
makers,"Temple said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Cracks Down on Oil Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has been determined
to crack down on the rampant oil smuggling which claims some 15
million U.S. dollars annually, or about 30 percent of Tanzania's
entire petroleum sales.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa vowed at a meeting here Wednesday that
his government will use every means, with the greater public
support, to succeed in its war against massive tax evasion in the
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the smuggling of petroleum products through
customs was on the rise with a growing trend toward the illegal
trade and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that 25 to 30 percent of the petroleum sales
business in this country is illegal due to tax evasion," said
Mkapa in his opening speech at the road stakeholders' meeting on
the partnership of public and private sectors in the
infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that the massive tax evasion in the petroleum
sector, which has an annual total fuel consumption at about
555,110 tons, was a serious set- back to government efforts to
create enabling conditions so that the economy can grow.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that smuggling across Tanzania's "porous"
borders was rampant because the entry points were not properly
patrolled.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tanzania announced several measures to curb the wave of
massive tax evasion in the petroleum industry, including the
introduction of a new technology of fuel marking known as the
"bicode".
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance, the Ministry of Energy and Minerals,
the Tanzania Revenue Authority and the Tanzania Petroleum
Development Corporation are consulting on the possibility of
introducing bicode to make it difficult for businessmen to cheat
the government.
</P>
<P>
The bicode technology has been largely successful in Uganda and
Kenya where revenue authorities have been able to tame illicit oil
trade and recorded substantial increases in tax collection.
</P>
<P>
It will also enable customs officers to differentiate pure
petroleum products from adulterated and transit-destined fuel by
dishonest traders. Areas notorious for the illegal trade include
Dar es Salaam, Arusha, Kilimanjaro, Tanga, Bukoba, Kigoma, Mwanza
and Mara.
</P>
<P>
The government has already applied the petroleum sector
regulations and revoked licenses of several oil marketing
companies which deliberately fail to pay taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Save World's Tallest Ancient Wooden Pagoda (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
start a massive restoration and salvation project to save the
world's tallest ancient wooden pagoda, which, in its 944 years of
existence, is in danger of collapsing.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined to save the wooden pagoda at all
costs," said Zhang Wenbin, director-general of the State Bureau of
Cultural Relics. "The final version of the restoration plan will
make no consideration of cost, as long as it works best for
protecting the pagoda and preserving its original look."
</P>
<P>
Standing 65.86 meters, the octagonal pagoda in Yingxian County
in north China's Shanxi Province is not only the tallest but also
the oldest wooden pagoda in China today. Compared with the
renowned Leaning Tower of Pisa in Italy, the wooden pagoda in
Yingxian is 115 years older and 11.36 meters taller. The pagoda
was listed as a cultural heritage under first-class state
protection in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the restoration project including an overall
estimate of the damage and geological exploration of the pagoda's
foundation are already near completion, and are expected to cost
nearly seven million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts on ancient architecture are working on three separate
restoration plans, and one will be selected with final approval
from an expert panel organized by the State Bureau of Cultural
Relics later this year.
</P>
<P>
Although it has successfully weathered nearly a thousand years
of climatic changes, the pagoda is now seriously unaligned, mainly
due to the damage done by numerous strong earthquakes and cannon
attacks. The first two stories of the pagoda are leaning
northeastward, and some of its wooden columns and parts are broken
or split.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Save World's Tallest Ancient Wooden Pagoda (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The increasing occurrence of earthquakes in the area also makes
it even more urgent to realign and restore the pagoda, according
to Cai Zejun, an expert on ancient architecture. "The pagoda is in
such poor condition that natural disasters such as gales or
earthquakes of high magnitude could topple the pagoda to the
ground," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the State Bureau of Cultural Relics has listed the
restoration of the wooden pagoda as a top priority for the
protection of ancient architecture this year, while the Shanxi
Provincial Government has set up a special restoration committee
to handle the project.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 noted experts in areas related to the restoration
of ancient buildings have been invited to the pagoda since late
last year in order to pool all possible expert wisdom to secure
the pagoda's existence for at least another 1,000 years, according
to Zhang Wenbin.
</P>
<P>
Three restoration drafts are being worked out for the present:
one for pure consolidation and reinforcement, one for
disassembling and reassembling all parts of the entire pagoda, and
the other for the partial disassembling and reassembling of the
first two stories of the pagoda.
</P>
<P>
Luo Zhewen, head of the expert panel on ancient architecture in
the State Bureau of Cultural Relics, said that as a measure of
caution, the final design will be submitted to the State Council
for approval and the bureau will have to apply for special state
funds to finance the project due to its massive scale and high
cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
