<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Call for Ban on Smuggling of Fossils (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese and foreign
scientists attending an international conference here called for
an immediate ban on the illegal trade of fossils worldwide as the
increasingly rampant smuggling has been detrimental to scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
They made the call at today's opening of the Fifth
International Meeting of the Society of Avian Paleontology and
Evolution and the Symposium on Jehol Biota in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
"Fossils are the most important samples for paleontologists,
and the random collection and smuggling of fossils is not only
illegal, but also damaging to resources for academic research,"
said Zhang Miman, a member of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
and chairman of the organization committee of the international
conference.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, large quantities of ancient animal fossils
have been discovered in southwest China's Yunnan Province and
Liaoning Province in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
In late 1993, fossils of Confuciusornis, one of the most
primitive birds in the world, were found in the western part of
Liaoning. Two years later, Chinese paleontologists discussed the
finding in the British academic journal "Nature." drawing wide
attention in international academic circles. However, fossils of
the primitive birds were soon found being sold in Japan and some
Western countries.
</P>
<P>
"I used to be so naive as to believe that Confuciusornis
fossils kept at the CAS were the only ones in the world," said
Zhou Zhonghe, a curator of bird fossils, who was among the first
Confuciusornis researchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Call for Ban on Smuggling of Fossils (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The smuggling of bird fossils began a dozen years ago and many
of them were brought out of China by traffickers. The reports on
the excavation of fossils of Mesozoic animals lured fossil
smugglers to eye the rare fossils of primitive birds and dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
"Unprofessional excavation of fossils is destructive, as much
important information is lost during the digging and can never be
recovered," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The smuggling of rare bird fossils has not been effectively
curbed, though great efforts have been made by the government.
According to CAS researchers, hundreds of Confuciusornis fossils
have been sold on the international market, together with fossils
of dinosaurs and aquatic reptiles.
</P>
<P>
According to China's Law on Cultural Relics, fossils of
primitive vertebrates and primitive human beings are placed under
state protection as cultural relics, and UNESCO has listed them as
cultural heritages.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, upon learning that China had prohibited the export of
primitive vertebrate fossils, Professor Peter Wellnhofer, a German
expert, posted notices in local fossil markets telling people that
it is illegal to trade in fossils from China. Storrs Olson, an
expert from the United States, said that major museums would never
buy fossils from unknown sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wang Yuanqing, a researcher from the CAS, said that
the rising number of cases of fossil fabrication has directly
threatened academic research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Rules on Flood Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Methods on
Compensation in Floodwater-Storing Areas, which was adopted by the
28th executive meeting of the State Council on May 23, has come
into force.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji signed a State Council degree to this effect
on May 27.
</P>
<P>
The methods, composed of five chapters and 26 articles, are
applicable for state-level floodwater-storing areas to compensate
financial losses of local residents so as to ensure their basic
necessities and restore normal production.
</P>
<P>
The compensations must be paid in accordance with the financial
capability of the state, it says.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, there are now 97 state-level
floodwater-storing zones across the country, including 40 in the
Yangtze River area, five in the Yellow River area, 26 in the Haihe
River area, and 26 in the Huaihe River area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
