<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Israel to Withdraw From Shebaa Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has urged Israel to withdraw from the Shebaa farms in
south Lebanon and to release Lebanese prisoners, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone talk with the U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
on Wednesday evening, Kharrazi stressed that any provocative move
by the Israeli regime may create a critical situation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the latest developments in south
Lebanon following the Israeli withdrawal last week.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed hope that the Lebanese Hezbollah will play a key
role in the future of the country, saying that the U.N. is trying
to collect humanitarian aids by different countries to help
reconstruct Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which declines to recognize Israel, supports the
Hezbollah guerrillas who led Lebanese resistance against Israel's
occupation. The guerrilla said it will continue to fight Israel if
it does not leave the Shebaa region.
</P>
<P>
Shebaa Farms, seized by Israel from Lebanon in the 1967 Middle
East war, are located on the Lebanese side of Mount Hermon which is
</P>
<P>
Syria's highest mountain but under Israeli occupation now. 
</P>
<P>
Israel argues that the Shebaa Farms belong to Syria, and that a
withdrawal from this area will be considered in peace talks with
Damascus when they resume. 
</P>
<P>
According to the British-French agreement on the Lebanese-
Palestinian border in 1923, the Shebaa Farms are not included in
the Lebanese side. But Beirut said Syria had already bequeathed the
farms to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
