<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa Becomes Major Conduit for World Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The East African region has
become a major illicit drug conduit connecting America, Europe and
other areas in the world, police officers have warned.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the police in Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda and Rwanda
concluded a three- day meeting here Wednesday, calling for joint
actions to crack down on the fast-growing drug dealings in the
region.
</P>
<P>
There is a worrying evidence that major drug barons are using
the region as a main transit route and destination for buyers
outside Africa, it was reported Thursday by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The British High Commissioner in Tanzania told the 8th
Operational Meeting on Drugs for the Directors of Criminal
Investigation Department and Heads of Anti-Narcotics Units for
East Africa that large, multi-kilo quantities of heroin are
staying in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Preventive measures are needed to be put in place before the
East African region comes to be seen as a safe warehouse and major
dealing center for hard drugs," Bruce Dinwiddy said.
</P>
<P>
Director of Criminal Investigation (DCI) in Tanzania,
Commissioner of Police Adadi Rajabu admitted the startling
revelation, saying most of the drugs seized in America and Europe
were traced back to the region.
</P>
<P>
"It is now evident that most of the said drugs could easily
find their way to Europe, America and other parts of the world
through ports and other exit points in East Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the East African region has experienced an increase in
illicit drugs related activities in the late 1980's and early
1990's due to the introduction of better means of communication.
</P>
<P>
"Prior to that period, our region had not yet established
itself as a major illicit drugs network of the world," he said,
noting that other than drugs such as heroin, cocaine, mandrax,
only Herbal Cannabis was largely consumed within member countries
in the region then.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting resolved to embark on exchange
programs for their law enforcer officers to conduct joint regional
training courses and to exchange drug related information.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that member states should ensure their legislation
allowed for pre-trial destruction of drugs and recognized the need
for the ratification of the protocol on combating drug trafficking
and abuse in East Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Trails World in Gender Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is the 14th poorest country
in the world on the gender disparity in education, according to
the background to National Strategy for Girls Education in the
east African country.
</P>
<P>
The strategy notes that despite the assistance from
international and local agencies as well as political will which
has brought powerful female leaders to the fore, Uganda's
achievement in advancing female education still falls short of the
typical indicators.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 146 developing countries rated on the Gender Human
Development Index, Uganda is relegated to 132nd place compared
with Kenya's 112th and Tanzania's 123rd position," said a New
Vision report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Its female adult literacy rate of 48 percent and female life
expectancy of 41 years trail behind both Tanzania and Kenya," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The strategy, funded by the United Nations Children Fund
(UNICEF), pointed out that drop-out rates were higher among girls
and that female enrolment was still lower than that of males at
all levels of education.
</P>
<P>
At primary education level, it put girls' enrolment at 47
percent compared with 53 percent for boys, and it widens to 32
percent for females and 68 percent for males at secondary level,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone to Consult International Community on Sankoh's Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) - Sierra Leonean government said
Wednesday that it would consult with the international community
to decide whether to put rebel leader Foday Sankoh on trial.
</P>
<P>
National Concord, a major Nigerian newspaper, Thursday quoted
the country's Information Minister Julius Spencer as saying in
Freetown on Wednesday that it is "a complex issue to decide
exactly what Sankoh should be tried for".
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a local radio interview with the minister as
saying that a decision would have to be taken on "whether to try
Sankoh locally or internationally".
</P>
<P>
He said Sierra Leone, relying heavily upon the international
community for assistance, did not want to make the decision on its
own.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh was detained in Freetown on May 17, about a week after
he fled his home in the capital following a shooting-out by his
bodyguards at demonstrators before the eyes of the UN soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The public in Freetown was recently angry at Sankoh' s
unsuccessful escape and required the government to try him.
</P>
<P>
During Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war, rebels led by
Sankoh killed tens of thousands of people and mutilated thousands
of civilians, but Sankoh was amnestied for the crimes under the
Lome peace accord signed last July in exchange of the
demobilization of his troops.
</P>
<P>
But the rebels had in fact broken the accord by attacking and
taking hostages of the UN peacekeepers in the country, said some
observers.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of the West African State (ECOWAS)
earlier this week resolved at a summit in Nigeria's capital Abuja
that Sankoh should be moved to "a safer place" in another country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
