<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Explore New Model for Traffic Management (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A primary student pushed a button,
the traffic light switched to red, and he walked across the street
leisurely with no sign of worry on his face.
</P>
<P>
This is a common scene at a busy crossing in Nanjing, capital
of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Several years ago, however, it was a completely different
picture at this very crossing. During after-school hours, the line
of students escorted by their teachers waited anxiously for the
traffic light.
</P>
<P>
How can it be? A tiny device that is capable of changing the
entire traffic conditions in the city?
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview, Yang Huanning, assistant minister of
Public Security, disclosed that the device is merely the tip of
the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
The iceberg, according to Yang, is the new urban traffic
management model being explored by Chinese police.
</P>
<P>
"While continuing to stick to its tradition of exerting arduous
efforts to manage traffic, Chinese police are trying to explore
new scientific managing models by applying advanced traffic
engineering theories," Yang stressed.
</P>
<P>
That's it! The new model!
</P>
<P>
The new model has seen its initial success in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, with a population of five
million, Nanjing has 300,000 motor vehicles and two million other
vehicles. In 1994, per capita road space in Nanjing was 4.7 sq.
meters, sharply lower than the seven-sq-meter national average,
and traffic jams dominated 80 percent of the crossings in the city
at that time.
</P>
<P>
Now, the situation is completely different. The city has few
traffic jams, few traffic accidents, and rare violations of
traffic regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Explore New Model for Traffic Management (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu Xiaoxiang, head of the Traffic Management Bureau of Nanjing
attributed these improvements to the support of the local
government and the adoption of scientific traffic management
methods.
</P>
<P>
"The city government calls for nearly all the departments in
the city to make joint efforts to tap the city's potential for
smooth transportation", Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Hu added that all major crossings in the city have already been
computerized. For instance, automatic cameras have been installed
at 120 major crossings to monitor traffic conditions, and multi-
directional traffic lights have been installed at 150 major
crossings to direct drivers more scientifically.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since the adoption of this device, the
average speed of automobiles moving on the 14 major roads during
rush hours has risen by 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
On February 26, the Ministry of Public Security and the
Ministry of Construction initiated the "Smooth Traffic Project" in
36 major cities and some medium and smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
Meng Hongwei, director of Traffic Management Bureau under the
Ministry of Public Security, also thought highly of the role of
the new model in this project.
</P>
<P>
"The project aims at realizing the transformation from the old
experience-oriented management model to the new sci-tech dominated
model," Meng said.
</P>
<P>
As public awareness of traffic rules needing enhancing, it is
of vital importance to set up "elaborate streets," streets
featuring high standard, high quality, and a high level of
management, Meng pointed out at the meeting on enforcement of the
project.
</P>
<P>
" 'The people's police serving people,' that is our motto. In
the implementation of the new model, we should be patient and
reasonable in fighting backward traffic practices, for it has
lasted for centuries in China," Meng stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
