<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The U.S.-based Lucent Technologies Inc., a research
and development arm of Bell, agreed on Wednesday to buy Chromatis
Networks for some 4.5 billion U.S. dollars, setting a new record
for the purchase of a company originating in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The value of the deal will rise to 4.8 billion dollars if
Chromatis, a developer of innovative optical-network technology for
metropolitan communications applications, meets certain performance
targets.
</P>
<P>
The payment will be in the form of some 78 million shares of
Lucent common stock. The 4.5-billion-dollar valuation is based on a
closing price of 58.125 dollars for Lucent stock on May 30.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cyprus government Wednesday decided to raise the
price of unleaded petrol from 0.378 Cyprus pound (0.612 U.S.
dollar) to 0.418 pound (0.677 dollar) a liter.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, Minister of Commerce, Industry and
Tourism Nicos Rolandis also said the price of super oil will rise
from 0.4 pound (0.648 dollar) to 0.44 pound (0.713 dollar) a liter.
The price of diesel will increase from 0.146 pound (0.237 dollar)
to 0.166 pound (0.269 dollar) a liter.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to annul fuel subsidies to the
island's national carrier Cyprus Airways.
</P>
<P>
The new price hikes came into effect as from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- First quarter results of Israel's major banks were
positive across the board, according to earning reports released
Wednesday by Bank Leumi, Israel Discount Bank and United Mizrahi
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The banks' activities in the capital markets increased
threefold, with increased investments in both provident and mutual
funds -- resulting in increased management fees for the banks --
and commissions from the high volume of general trading.
</P>
<P>
Analysts question whether similar results will be produced in
the quarters to come.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish banks suffered a loss of 566 million U.S.
dollars in 1999, reported Anatolia News Agency on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics in a booklet of Banks Union of Turkey "
Our Banks-1999," a total of 18 banks were operating in Turkey as of
the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The total assets of these banks increased 96 percent to 72
quadrillion Turkish Liras in 1999 or 14 percent to 133.5 billion U.
S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The average of total TL assets in national income rose from 69
percent to 92 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate dropped to a seasonally
adjusted 8.6 percent of the workforce in the first quarter of this
year, in comparison with 8.9 percent in the fourth quarter and 8.7
percent in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
This is the second consecutive quarterly decline from the 9
percent rate recorded during the July-September period.
Unemployment rate reached a record high of 11.2 percent in 1992,
then declined during the following four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
