<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Muslim Brotherhood Suspects Arrested in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian police have arrested three
suspected members of the banned Muslim Brotherhood in the north of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution at El-Manzala in Dakahlia Governorate, 90
kilometers north of Cairo, ordered the detention of the three
people Wednesday on charges of promoting the ideology of the
Brotherhood, Al Akhbar daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Video cassettes, books and other publications for propagating
Brotherhood ideology were seized in the houses of the three
suspects in El-Manzala, the pro-government newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
The detainees will face several counts of incitement, including
attempts to overthrow the ruling regime, possession of outlawed
books and embracing the ideas of the banned group.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 members of the Muslim Brotherhood have been
arrested since October 1999, dozens of whom since the beginning of
May, in a growing government crackdown on the movement.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's largest Islamic fundamentalist
group, was banned in 1954 by former President Gamal Abdel Nasser,
but it enjoys intermittent periods of official tolerance as it does
not advocate violence in attempting to install a strict Islamic
rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
