<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Seeks Arab Support for OIC Top Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has turned to Arab countries
for backing its candidate for the post of secretary-general of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) after winning a
majority support from the Asian group.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon hosted for Arab ambassadors in Ankara Wednesday,
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem asked for Arab support, which is viewed
as crucial in Turkey's candidate Yasar Yakis' election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Cem told reporters before the luncheon that Turko-Arab relations
are one of the priorities of Turkey's foreign policy, adding that
Turkey had been focusing on improving its ties with Arab countries
in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
Without elaborating, Cem said that misunderstanding between
Turkey and Arab countries had been eradicated. But he was
apparently referring to the Arab complaints about Turkey's military
ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's flirtation with the Arabs came after Ankara reached an
understanding with Bangladesh on raising an Asian candidate for the
OIC's top post.
</P>
<P>
The OIC secretary-general is a four-year post which rotates
among the three groups of countries within the 55-member Islamic
body, namely the Arab, Asian and African groups. Turkey is in the
Asian group.
</P>
<P>
Under OIC standard practice, since the outgoing Moroccan
Secretary-General Azzeddine Laraki is not seeking a second term, it
is presumably the Asian group's turn now to appoint someone to the
office.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was the first country to announce its candidate for
the post, naming its Parliament Speaker Humayun Rashid Chowdhry,
and Turkey announced its contender secondly.
</P>
<P>
Turkey believes that its candidate is the most qualified and
competent contender, said Cem. Yasar Yakis, a career diplomat with
a vast experience of Middle East affairs as well as international
organizations, speaks fluent Arabic, French and English, the three
official languages in the organization.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Faruk Logoglu visited Bangladesh
last week to hold political consultations with his Bangladesh
counterpart on the issue.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the two countries agreed to support an
Asian candidate, instead of an Arab choice, in the upcoming
elections for the leading OIC post, but neither is willing at this
point to withdraw its candidate.
</P>
<P>
Muslim countries, which have close relations with both Turkey
and Bangladesh, are trying to persuade the two members of the Asain
group to compromise and withdraw one candidate in favor of the
other.
</P>
<P>
Turkish diplomatic sources say that Ankara, which has already
received the backings of nine out of 17 countries, told Bangladesh
that Turkey was in a more advantageous position in terms of support
from the Asian group.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has reportedly made it clear that it would support
Turkish candidate in case that its own loses his chance in the
race.  The Jiddah-based OIC is scheduled to convene a foreign
ministerial meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, on June 27-30 to
choose the new secretary-general, who will be approved at the next
OIC summit in Qatar on November 12-14 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Germany Sign Security Cooperation Agreement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Germany have signed a
security cooperation agreement on jointly fighting organized crime,
drug trafficking and human smuggling, Anatolia News Agency reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turan Genc, director general of the Turkish Security Forces,
held talks on Wednesday with his German counterpart Ulrich Kersten,
who paid a two-day visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after their meetings, the two sides called
on the security organizations of all countries to cooperate closely
to fight against cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish police chief said that the close cooperation between
Turkey and Germany in this field is deep-rooted, being kept in a
good way.
</P>
<P>
During their meetings, Genc said that they discussed how to take
efficient measures to implement the agreement in curbing these
criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
The German police head said that Germany has attached importance
to conducting international cooperation in the fight against cross-
border crimes.
</P>
<P>
"We want to hold seminars and exchange our experience," he said,
expressing congratulations to Turkish police on the success of
their operations against drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Germany have close ties in political, economic and
cultural fields. There have been 3 million Turkish citizens living
in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
