<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fijian Military Says Major Breakthrough Imminent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A major breakthrough has been made
in the bid to resolve Fiji's hostage crisis, a military spokesman
said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
"We have had a very major breakthrough," said military
spokesman Eroni Volavola after a meeting between coup leader
George Speight and army Commander Frank Bainimarama.
</P>
<P>
"I think we can safely say that within the next 24 to 36 hours
you will start to see a lot of very positive things coming out of
parliament," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Speight and Bainimarama was the first face
to face talks between the pair since the hostage crisis began on
May 19.
</P>
<P>
The details of any peace deal remain unclear, although Volavola
hinted one concession was that Speight supporters would be part of
an interim civilian government to take over when the military
regime stood aside.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility is there," he said of the likelihood
appointment of Speight's men to government roles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
