<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, MILF to Hold Another Talks Over Proposed  Autonomy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government and Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) peace negotiators agreed Thursday
to hold another round of talks later this month over the
government proposal of autonomy for the MILF, the government said.
</P>
<P>
Both panels will meet again on June 28 to settle the proposal
over autonomy for the MILF, chief government negotiator Edgardo
Batenga told reporters after ending their fourth round formal
negotiations in Mindanao Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The autonomy proposal, according to the chief negotiator, is
believed to be the only solution to end the armed conflict in
Mindanao"that is consistent and compatible with the Philippine
Constitution."
</P>
<P>
"The proposal has already been accepted by both sides in
principle,but what we are more concerned now is the time frame,"
said Batenga.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the MILF has some 20 days to study and answer the
proposal presented to them since President Joseph Estrada earlier
set the deadline as up to the end of this month for the two panes
to wrap up their talks.
</P>
<P>
Moner Bajunaid, MILF acting panel chairman, said that they are
also working hard to submit comments and counter-proposals to fine
tune lapses in the government peace proposal.
</P>
<P>
The two sides resumed their peace talks in Cotabato,
Maguindanao province Tuesday after the negotiation has been
stalled by clashes of government forces and MILF rebels in the
Mindanao area.
</P>
<P>
The armed conflicts between the two sides over the past few
months have killed more than 150 soldiers while having some 500
others wounded and about 200,000 civilians displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
