<HEADLINE> Gunman Releases Two Children at Wasserbillig EDS-Updates with details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The gunman holding more than 20
kids hostage on Thursday released two children including the
youngest, a two-year-old girl, police said.
</P>
<P>
The released children now totaled 10. The children held hostage
are all aged under eight.
</P>
<P>
The man, armed with a pistol, a hand grenade and a knife, was
still facing off with the Luxembourg police at Wasserbillig in
eastern Luxembourg bordering Germany and had demanded to be flown
to Libya with around 20 million francs (about 220,000 U.S. dollars)
in return for the release of the 29 children he had taken hostage
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He also took three adult females from the nursery school as
hostage.
</P>
<P>
The man, only identified as an Algerian national who came to
settle in Luxembourg in 1982 and a father of two, has a history of
mental illness but he told the police that he does not want any
harm to come to the children.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 Portuguese children are among the hostages. French,
German and Luxembourg children are also being held captive since
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The police has cordoned off the nursery school and ambulances
and fire engines are standing by near the school building.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg Interior Minister Michel Wolter has instructed
earlier that the hostage taking incident be ended without violence.
Social workers are negotiating with the gunman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
