Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- Mustafa Bumin was elected on Wednesday as the new presiding
judge of the Turkish Constitutional Court, a post vacated by Ahmet
Sezer upon his election as Turkish President.
</P>
<P>
Bumin, who was appointed a member of the Constitutional Court in
1992 by late President Turgut Ozal, was born in Kayseri, a central
Anatolian province, in 1940. He graduated from Ankara University's
Law Faculty and in 1967 held a senior post in the government.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Education Minister Metin Bostancioglu was outraged on
Wednesday by the skyrocketing increases imposed by private schools
on their tuition to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
He called on parents to take their children from these schools
and enroll them to foundation schools which made 25 percent
increases on their yearly fees.
</P>
<P>
