<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Moves to Lower Medicine Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez Jr. said in a radio
interview that the government wants more accurate estimates of
medicine prices and increased competitiveness in the bidding
process.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the practice of giving agency estimates for drugs
and medicines has not been used. We're perfecting the process by
which we can make accurate estimates so the accurate estimation of
prices can be carried out," Romualdez said.
</P>
<P>
He added the government will still import lower-priced
medicines to pressure more pharmaceutical firms to bring down the
prices of their products.
</P>
<P>
"This is only a part of our campaign to lower prices. By
broadening our sources of medicines, we will further lower the
prices Romualdez said.
</P>
<P>
In line with his commitment to provide the poor with quality
health care, President Joseph Estrada earlier urged the Department
of Health and other concerned agencies to find ways of pulling
down medicine prices in the country, which he noted, cost ten
times more than those sold in other Asian countries, such as India.
</P>
</TEXT>
