<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Expand Relief Food Plan in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) is to
expand its emergency relief food operations in Kenya, especially
to cover 18 districts severely hit by drought.
</P>
<P>
The agency, through its emergency operation program, is
distributing 75, 000 tons of food in Turkana, Marsabit and Mandera
districts in northern Kenya at a cost of 43 million U.S. dollars,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
WFP deputy country director David Flether said Wednesday in
Garissa town,
</P>
<P>
Kenya's North Eastern Province, that his organization would
supply more food to cover up drought-hit districts in the next
six months.
</P>
<P>
He said in the next 10 days, the food program and partners
would launch an international appeal for help to those living in
the northern parts of Kenya who are the worst hit.
</P>
<P>
Flether noted that successive failure of both long and short
rains in many parts of Kenya had shattered the traditional
drought-coping mechanism in these districts.
</P>
<P>
Just last week, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi appealed to
international donors for relief food, saying that 23 million
Kenyans, 80 percent of the population, were likely to starve
following the failure of the long rains in the current planting
season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
