<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's War Veterans Refuse to Leave Occupied Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Chairman of the Zimbabwe
National Liberation War Veterans Association Mike Moyo Wednesday
said members of the association will not leave the farms they
occupied despite calls by Minister of Home Affairs Dumiso Dabengwa
to vacate the farms.
</P>
<P>
Only President Robert Mugabe has the authority to order the war
veterans off the farms, he told a press conference here in Harare.
</P>
<P>
However, Moyo said that his association has called upon its
members who have occupied farms to ensure that their demonstration
remains peaceful.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans should refrain from violence, he said.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans have occupied about 1,000 white farms since
February this year.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Dabengwa said the government does not expect war
veterans to resist vacating farms they are occupying once the
state starts resettling people under the amended Land Acquisition
Act.
</P>
<P>
The minister could not say whether he would order the police to
eject the war veterans if they refuse to budge as he is positive
that the occupiers would move out on their own.
</P>
<P>
According to the amended Land Acquisition Act, the government
will acquire farms without paying compensation for land.
</P>
<P>
War veterans leader Chenjerai Hunzvi issued an ultimatum to the
 government at the weekend to allocate land to ex-combatants and
villagers before the June 24 and 25 elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
