<HEADLINE> U.S. Dream Team Unveils Pre-Olympic Training Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. men's Olympic basketball
team will open its pre-Olympic training on August 26 with five
exhibition games, the NBA Asia Limited said in a press release
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
During the 21 days leading to the Olympic Games slated for
September 16 to October 1 in Sydney, the U.S. men cagers will gear
up their weaponry through games against national teams from Canada,
Japan, Spain and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Americans will play first against Canada on August 31 in
Hawaii, meet Spain on September 5 and Japan on September 6 in
Saitama, located approximately 30 minutes outside of downtown
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
On September 9, the United States will play Olympic host
Australia in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Along with their men peers, the American women basketballers
will also tune up their Olympic preparations from Hawaii to Japan
and Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic men's basketball competition will start on
September 17, with quarterfinals slated for September 28,
semifinals on September 29 and the gold and bronze medal games on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Defending champions the United States will play in Group A
along with China, France, Italy, Lithuania and New Zealand, while
Group B features Angola, Australia, Canada, Russia, Spain and the
1998 world champions Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
During the Olympic Games, the United States will first play
China on September 17 before meeting Italy, Lithuania, New Zealand
and France every three days.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member U.S. men's national team includes Ray Allen of
Milwaukee Bucks, Vin Baker of Seattle SuperSonics, Vince Carter of
Toronto Raptors, Tim Duncan of San Antonio Spurs, Kevin Garnett of
Minnesota Timberwolves, Tim Hardaway of Maimi Heat, Grant Hill of
Detroit Pistons, Allan Houston of New York Knicks, Jason Kidd of
Phoenix Suns, Alonzo Mourning of Miami Heat, Gary Payton of
Seattle SuperSonics and Steve Smith of Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
Rudy Tomjanovich, Houston Rockets head coach since 1991, will
serve as head coach of the 2000 U.S.A. Basketball Senior National
Team, and Philadelphia 76ers head coach Larry Brown will be one of
three assistant coaches. 
</P>
