<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Leads Professor to Riches (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 1 (Xinhua) --Professor Zhang Tingbi of the Life
Science College of Wuhan University in central China's Hubei
Province no longer goes from company to company seeking research
financing, as he did eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
Zhang has been certified by a local accountants office as
having 131 million yuan (about 15.8 million U.S. dollars) worth of
assets from the intellectual property rights he possesses in a
Wuhan-based conglomerate which produces blood-enhancing health
products.
</P>
<P>
"The intellectual property rights system has kept improving in
China, and this will encourage more and more researchers to
actively apply their scientific findings to industrial production
and transform them into corporate stakes," said the 62-year-old
biology professor.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, when Zhang was doing research on plant pigmentation,
he had the idea to spread the application of porphyrin iron
technology by using biological methods to mass produce porphyrin
iron, an effective and low-cost agent for preventing and curing
iron-deficiency anemia.
</P>
<P>
His idea won support from a group of private businessmen who
invested 500,000 yuan (about 60,240 U.S. dollars) to finance Zhang
's research and development. A popular blood-enhancing health
product called "Hongtaokei Blood-Enhancing Agent" was soon
developed. Now, advertising for the blood-enhancing product can
be seen from crowded football fields to remote countryside houses.
</P>
<P>
The Hongtaokei Group, considered the largest private business
in the city of Wuhan, decided in 1996 that Professor Zhang should
have 10 percent of the group's stock, and Zhang was also elected a
director of the eight-member board of directors for the group.
</P>
<P>
Annual sales of the Hongtaokei-brand blood-enhancing agent now
exceeds one billion yuan (about 120 million U.S. dollars), with
more than 100 million yuan (about 12 million U.S. dollars) paid in
taxes annually.
</P>
<P>
In addition to technological stock rights, Professor Zhang also
receives an annual salary of 120,000 yuan (about 14,458 U.S.
dollars), owns a town villa worth four million yuan (481,928 U.S.
dollars) and a limousine worth more than 800,000 yuan (96,386 U.S.
dollars). This constitutes a striking contrast to the traditional
image of Chinese professors who used to be poor while despising
any involvement in economic activities.
</P>
<P>
"Eight years ago, I was always short of money and worried a lot
over research financing," Zhang recalled, "in most cases, I could
not manage research and teaching simultaneously with the limited
financing I got."
</P>
<P>
Despite his new-found riches, the millionaire professor still
lives a simple life on the campus of the University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Leads Professor to Riches (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fact that scientists who have become prosperous with their
research achievements have been pushed to the front stage by the
growth of high- and new-tech industries symbolizes that knowledge
economy will break through the obstacles of thought, property
rights, and the distribution system.
</P>
<P>
University professors and government officials alike are
encouraged by Professor Zhang's story. Professor Lu Zhongmei of
the Zhongnan (Central-South China) Institute of Political Science
and Law in Wuhan said social recognition of "scientific tycoons"
will be conducive to forming a range of new concepts.
</P>
<P>
Heralding the phenomenon of Professor Zhang Tingbi as an
epitome of developing China's fledgling knowledge economy, Chinese
economist Li Guang believed that under a knowledge economy, the
intellectual property rights system will help turn knowledge into
capital.
</P>
<P>
China has been swept by a wave of stockholding transformation
in the past decade, coupled with the establishment of capital
markets and the expansion of reforms regarding property rights and
income distribution.
</P>
<P>
Ownership of private assets and distribution according to
corporate stock proportions are now both protected by Chinese laws.
</P>
<P>
"Regulations on Promoting Application of Scientific and
Technological Achievements" published last year stipulate that
factors of production such as technology and management expertise
are allowed and encouraged to be included in the distribution of
income, and the proportion of technological shares in the total
capital of an enterprise is raised from 20 percent to 35 percent
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Governments at various levels have been busy drafting measures
to introduce mechanisms that will encourage scientific and
technological innovations in state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"China has been creating a nice environment for the development
of a knowledge economy," said economist Li Guang, citing Professor
Zhang Tingbi's success as an evidence.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the country has been reforming its academic
institutions, which will soon see a great number of scientific and
technological workers no longer depending on state finance for
salaries, but turning to the market for subsistence.
</P>
<P>
Economist Li Guang is confident that if thousands of scientific
tycoons can be brought about and scientific and technological
workers become fully market-aware, the springtime for China's
knowledge economy arrives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Straits Anti-Earthquake Forum Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Cross-Straits Forum on Urban
Earthquake Prevention and Disaster Relief opened this morning in
Fuzhou, capital of east China's Fujian Province, which faces
Taiwan across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 seismologists from China's mainland and Taiwan
have gathered here to attend the two-day forum.
</P>
<P>
They will delve into such topics as earthquake prevention, the
application of new and high technologies in earthquake prevention,
disaster relief and rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
Both the mainland and Taiwan are frequently hit by earthquakes.
Seismologists from both sides of the straits have increased
cooperation and exchanges in earthquake research and prevention
over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
At least four cross-Straits forums on earthquake prevention
have been held in Beijing, Xi'an and Taipei.  
</P>
