<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan's Future Lies in Reunification: Army Daily (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The future of Taiwan lies in the
ultimate reunification of the motherland, according to a signed
article in today's Liberation Army Daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
At present, the island of Taiwan at the crossroads. "Both
history and reality indicate to us that Taiwan's future lies in
the ultimate reunification of the motherland," the article said.
</P>
<P>
Only the reunification with the motherland will ensure Taiwan a
broad international space, respectable world status, and give the
Taiwan residents the dignity and honor of being Chinese, it noted.
</P>
<P>
After nearly a century of hard struggle, the Chinese people
have finally stood up, and the country is emerging as a big
country in the world after half a century development, it said.
</P>
<P>
As one of the five permanent members of the United Nations
Security Council and the biggest developing country in the world,
China has been playing a major role in the peace and development
of mankind, and has won high respect and honor from the
international community, the article said.
</P>
<P>
History demonstrates that Taiwan's fate has been closely linked
to the fate of the motherland, and a strong and united motherland
has always been the ultimate home of Taiwan, it said.
</P>
<P>
The island can achieve real independence, equality, and
security along with the motherland only when the country is
completely reunited on the basis of the one-China principle, the
article said.
</P>
<P>
It is only reunification with the motherland that will ensure
Taiwan's economy a solid basis of steady growth and safeguard the
prosperity and happiness of the Taiwan people, the article said. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan's Future Lies in Reunification: Army Daily (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a typical island economy, Taiwan is heavily dependent on
foreign trade, which accounts for over 96 percent of its total
gross domestic products (GDP). On the other hand, the mainland has
become the world's largest new market with a population of nearly
1.3 billion people, the article said.
</P>
<P>
The globalization and regionalization of the world economy
means that the island's hope of sustained economic growth lies in
the motherland, which has already been demonstrated by the
development of cross-Straits economic relations over the past 20
years, it said.
</P>
<P>
It is only reunification with the motherland that will ensure
Taiwan long-term peace and security amid the great waves of the
Pacific, the article noted.
</P>
<P>
From a geopolitical point of view, Taiwan has an important
position in Asia-Pacific strategy, and has been an area of
contention among the world's major powers. As a hilly island,
Taiwan also lacks strategic depth and is susceptible to outside
attacks, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Facts have shown that separated from the motherland, the island
of Taiwan will not have the capacity to defend itself against the
tempestuous waves of the Pacific, and will ultimately fall prey to
big powers.
</P>
<P>
"Only a united and strong motherland will always be the
powerful guarantor of Taiwan's peace and security," the Liberation
Army Daily stressed.
</P>
<P>
The complete reunification of the motherland represents an
irresistible historical trend, and will benefit both sides of the
Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Proponents of "Taiwan independence" should bear in mind that
any attempt to split the island from the motherland will meet the
strong opposition of the entire Chinese people, who are ready to
defend the motherland's sovereign and territorial integrity with
life and blood, the article said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Vice-Chairperson Calls for Enhanced Relics Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Peng Peiyuan, vice-chairperson of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
has called for enhanced protection of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
During her recent inspection of cultural relics protection in
Shanxi province, Peng said that the general public should further
raise its awareness of relics protection and departments concerned
must strengthen their management capability.
</P>
<P>
The northern China province of Shanxi boasts over 3,500
cultural relics sites, many of which are of high historical and
artistic value.
</P>
<P>
While speaking highly of the province's efforts in the area of
relics protection, Peng said that all localities should further
implement the law on cultural relics protection, and deal properly
with the relationship between protection and economic development.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more efforts should be taken to give a full
play to the role of cultural relics in public education and
scientific research, Peng said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Output, Exports in May Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's oil output and exports showed
steady increase in May, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The INA quoted Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid as saying
that Iraq's oil output in May reached 3.1 million barrels per day
(bpd), compared with 2.63 million bpd in April and 2.16 million bpd
in March.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, Iraq's oil output capacity will be able
to reach 3.3 million bpd, Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraq's oil exports totalled 2.5 million bpd in May,
800,000 bpd up from the figure of March.
</P>
<P>
According to the oil minister, under the seventh phase of the U.
N. oil-for-food program due to end this month, Iraq is going to
export 350 million barrels of oil, bringing a record revenue of 85
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq has fulfilled its commitments toward the contracts of
marketing oil under the seventh phase of the oil-for-food deal,"
Rashid was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Iraq's accusation of the U.S. and British
delegates at the U.N. Sanctions Committee who put on hold contracts
Iraq signed with foreign companies to import oil equipment and
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
During the fifth, sixth and seventh phase of the U.N. oil-for-
food deal, Iraq signed contracts worth 1.5 billion dollars with
foreign companies to rehabilitate Iraq's oil industry, but only 770
million dollars worth of contracts were approved, said Rashid.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly condemned the U.S. and Britain of impeding
the implementation of the U.N. oil-for-food program by deliberately
shelving contracts Iraq signed with foreign countries to import
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies to offset the
crippling impacts of the decade-long U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to import basic goods in
an exemption to the stringent sanctions imposed on Iraq after its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
