<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Even if a framework for a final status accord is reached with
the Palestinians in the near future, the question of Jerusalem will
be left unresolved, Israeli Minister in Prime Minister's Office
Haim Ramon, responsible for Jerusalem affairs, acknowledged
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ramon, interviewed on Israel's Channel One Wednesday night, said
that "if there is an agreement, it will not include the issue of
Jerusalem, because I do not believe it is possible to resolve this
delicate matter at this point."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and his Israeli
team will hold a third and presumably last round of Stockholm back-
channel talks with their Palestinian counterparts on the framework
agreement in Israel on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The right-wing associations behind the plan to build a Jewish
neighborhood in East Jerusalem's Abu Dis are now organizing to set
up greenhouses or an agricultural farm, security sources told
Ha'aretz.
</P>
<P>
The associations also plan to have guards and maintenance
workers living on the site, hoping in this way to guarantee the
Jewish hold on it even before the final approval of detailed plans
for the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the army, police and Shin Bet security service
all recommend erecting a fence between Jerusalem and the Arab
neighborhoods on its border to be handed to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will complain to U.S.
President Bill Clinton that the Palestinians are foot-dragging in
negotiations, as the latest round of peace efforts move to Lisbon,
and the Stockholm back-channel talks resume in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Barak brought forward his meeting with Clinton, which will took
place in Lisbon, to Thursday morning, instead of an evening meeting
originally planned for Berlin.
</P>
<P>
This is so he can rush back to Israel for Jerusalem Day
celebrations to mark Israel's 1967 capture of the city, which
remains at the heart of the dispute with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- A bill setting a seven-year jail sentence for women who pray
at the Western Wall plaza and wear prayer shawls, blow the shofar
or read aloud from the Torah, was passed Wednesday by the Knesset
(Parliament) plenum in its preliminary reading.
</P>
<P>
The bill, sponsored by United Torah Judaism (UTJ) faction, came
in response to a Supreme Court ruling last week allowing the Women
of the Wall group to conduct public prayers at the Wall.
</P>
<P>
Many of the secular Knesset members responded with rage. One
Israel Coalition whip Ophir Pines-Paz said the members of the UTJ
faction have forgotten that they live in a democratic and
egalitarian society in which people are not imprisoned for their
gender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
