<HEADLINE> Manila Optimistic of Progress in Talks With MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said in a radio speech that
the government will do its part to beat the June 30 deadline for
reaching a settlement as set by President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
"We can't draw yet the whole picture, but we are hopeful some
objectives of our president can be achieved," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada had instructed government negotiators and
their MILF counterparts to reach a peace agreement, or at least
make substantial progress in the peace efforts, by June 30.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said the government, which is seeking genuine and long-
lasting peace in Mindanao, would not settle for any shortcut.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking for a long-term solution. Aside from a military
solution, we want to put in place economic measures to address the
root causes of the problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
Government and MILF negotiators are now putting the final
touches on a joint communique summarizing the highlights of their
two-day talks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides resumed their peace talks in Cotabato,
Maguindanao province Tuesday after the negotiation has been
stalled by clashes of government forces and MILF rebels in the
Mindanao area over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
The armed conflicts have killed more than 150 soldiers while
having some 500 others wounded and about 200,000 civilians
displaced. 
</P>
