<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Mining Sector Declines by 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's mining sector, one of the
country' s largest foreign exchange earners, has declined by 7.1
percent largely as a result of low international prices of
minerals, the weekly Business reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the latest Treasury monthly bulletin
indicated significant cuts in the production of a number of
minerals in the country, with asbestos output dropped by 37.1
percent, black granite by 97.6 percent, coal by 9 percent and
copper by 77.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Beside low international prices for metals and minerals, the
mining sector has become less profitable due to the flat exchange
rate while the rise in the rate of inflation has also put pressure
on the production costs, which have been worsened by the critical
shortage of fuel facing the country.
</P>
<P>
A number of mining houses, particularly those listed on the
stock market, have issued cautionary statements to their
shareholders over the impact that the prevailing harsh economic
environment has had on their businesses.
</P>
<P>
Some mining houses have also suspended or cut back on their
exploration activities because of cash flow problems, while others
have reduced their production levels.
</P>
<P>
The mining sector contributes over 8 percent to Zimbabwe's
gross domestic product and employs over 50,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Maize Harvest Expected to Increase by 12 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) region expects a maize harvest of 18.82 million
tons this year, 12 percent more than last year's output of 16.76
million tons, the daily Herald newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is likely to have produced just enough for its own
needs, while South Africa and Malawi will have surpluses to
compensate for deficits in the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
Maize prospects for the 1999-2000 season are generally brighter
than last year despite devastation caused by flooding in Zimbabwe,
southern Mozambique and parts of South Africa, Swaziland and
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
According to a food security update by the SADC, maize
production in South Africa is anticipated to reach 9.63 million
tons this year as against 7.11 million tons last year, while in
Zimbabwe the maize output is expected to increase from 1.52
million tons last year to 2.13 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
