<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Poorer Than 30 Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The standards of living in many
African countries are worse today than they were at independence
in the 1960s, a recent report by the World Bank indicated.
</P>
<P>
"Average income per capita is lower than that at the end of
1960s," the East African Standard daily Thursday quoted the report
entitled "Can Africa Claim the 21st Century?" as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The region's total income is not much more than Belgium's, and
is divided among 48 countries with a median gross domestic product
(GDP) of just over 2 billion U.S. dollars -- about the output of a
town of 60,000 in a rich country," the report said.
</P>
<P>
With its rapidly growing population, the continent needs to
grow by at least five percent per annum just to maintain current
poverty levels, the report said, noting that nearly half of the
continent's people are now living below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
"Africa accounts for barely 1 percent of global GDP and only 2
percent of world trade," the report said. "Its share of global
manufactured exports is almost zero." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
