<HEADLINE> Hostage-Taking Crisis Continues in Luxembourg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A 39-year-old man, armed with a
pistol, a hand grenade and a knife, was still facing off the
police with 23 nursery school children as hostage in eastern
Luxembourg on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police said the gunman, born in Algeria, has demanded to be
flown to Libya with around 10 million francs (about 220,000 U.S.
dollars) in return for the release of the children between four
and seven years of age, according to local television reports.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg police confirmed that negotiations with the gunman
was still going on after Luxembourg Interior Minister Michel
Wolter had instructed that the hostage incident be ended without
violence.
</P>
<P>
The hostage-taking took place on Wednesday at Wasserbillig near
the Luxembourg-Germany border.
</P>
<P>
The gunman was said to have become a Luxembourg citizen in 1982
but was said to have a history of mental problems. He also took
three adults from the day-care center as hostages.
</P>
<P>
Of the children taken hostage, some are from Germany, France
and Portugal besides those from Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that a total of 20 children and two adults
were taken hostage. The figures were later changed to 29 children
and three teachers in the nursery school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
