<HEADLINE> Former Residence of American Writer Opens to Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The former residence of American
writer Pearl S. Buck, a Nobel laureate for literature, opened to
visitors Wednesday at Nanjing University in east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people, including Kathleen Bowman, dean of Buck's
alma mater Randolph-Macon Woman's College in the United States,
and Meredith Richardson, chairman of the Pearl S. Buck
International Foundation, attended the unveiling ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Pearl Buck (1892-1973) spent nearly 40 years in China. She
taught English at Nanjing University for 12 years and completed
all her major books here.
</P>
<P>
Buck wrote several dozens novels set in China and translated
the Chinese novel All Men Are Brothers into English.
</P>
<P>
Many critics have said that her novels reveal the real China to
Western readers.  
</P>
