<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF New Chief Vows to Listen more </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund (
IMF) will listen more to the people and the authorities so that it
can give good advice, IMF's new Managing Director Horst Koehler
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with Thai Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai, Koehler said he thinks the role of the IMF is not "
imposing," but "really giving good advice based on more listening
to the people and the authorities" and produce measures conducive
to strong growth.
</P>
<P>
Taking over the post of managing director of the IMF four weeks
ago, Koehler said one of the lessons he learned from the Asian
crisis is that the IMF should "listen better" to the people and
the authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, he refused to comment whether IMF's prescription for
Thailand is wrong, while admitting that the IMF has to do more on
crisis prevention.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is going to graduate from the IMF-led assistance
program, worth 17.2 billion U.S. dollars, next month, which it
received after its currency baht collapsed in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the fund, Thailand had to adhere to strict IMF
economic performance standards, with its compliance periodically
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
But the IMF was accused of applying inappropriate conditions on
the package, including placing stringent curbs on government
spending, and miscalculating the depth of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
It was also criticized for applying the same solution to the
very different crises occurring in Thailand, South Korea and
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Thailand stopped drawing funds from the package last June,
after receiving a total of 14.2 billion dollars in credits from
multilateral and bilateral contributors under the program.
</P>
<P>
Describing both his meetings with Chuan and Finance Minister
Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda Wednesday as "fruitful," Koehler said he is
encouraged that the Thai economy is on the path of continued
recovery.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, to make the recovery sustainable, the Thai
government should further carry out the restructuring of the
banking sector, with focus on the improvement of the non-
performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Koehler also voiced support to the Chiang Mai Initiative,
saying it is "complementary to the IMF's own understanding of its
preparedness to support the countries."
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers from China, Japan, South Korea and the 10
members of the Association of the Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
agreed last month in Thailand's northern city of Chiang Mai on
establishing a regional financing arrangement to prevent future
currency crises and to provide short-term balance of payments
support for countries in need.
</P>
<P>
Koehler said he supports any initiative that will help the
countries in the region to improve their economies and to get out
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is the first leg of Koehler's five-nation Asian tour.
He is going on to visit China, South Korea, Indonesia and India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0234 </DOCNO>
