<HEADLINE> NZ Trade Unions Condemn Coup in Fiji </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of all the major
New Zealand trade unions met and adopted a resolution here
Thursday, condemning the "actions of the terrorists and their use
of arms and hostages to force the overthrow of the democratically
elected government and constitution of Fiji."
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called for "an immediate release of the
hostages, reinstatement of constitutional democracy and the return
of all basic human rights and freedoms."
</P>
<P>
It said the combined unions have noted the intention of the New
Zealand Government to institute various sanctions and supported
the actions announced by the government.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to persuade all New Zealand businesses trading
with Fiji to suspend trading, to persuade New Zealanders to
boycott Fiji as a tourist destination, to persuade the NZ Tourism
Board and media organizations to cease advertising and promotion
of Fiji, to persuade sporting bodies to cease sporting contacts,
and to raise funds for the Fijian Trades Union Congress in its
struggle. 
</P>
