<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Five Kenyan farmers have been
sentenced to a five-month imprisonment each after they admitted
slaughtering and eating a hippo to avert hunger on May 29.
</P>
<P>
Although they were first offenders, they posed a threat to the
hippo population, the East African Standard newspaper Thursday
quoted the prosecutor at a Nyahururu district court in central
Kenya as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Kiama, the prosecutor, told the court that 70 hippos
had been killed in that district during the past two months.
</P>
<P>
However, the five accused said that they had tried to rescuing
the hippo,
</P>
<P>
who was stuck in the mud, but failed to move it.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that they had no alternative but to slaughter the
animal and take its meat to home.
</P>
<P>
The court was also told that how game rangers and police
officers spotted a dead hippo in the mud and following the foot
marks they found the hippo meat in the accused's kitchens.
</P>
