<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants to Defer Opening Up of Automotive Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said his country wants the implementation of the
ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) agreement for the automotive sector
to be deferred to 2005 from 2003.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is requesting that the agreement be effective in 2005
instead of 2003, for the benefit of the national car industry, the
prime minister told reporters in Langkawi after the presentation
of the ASEAN Kart Prix 2000 Cup.
</P>
<P>
"Our automotive industry is still small compared with other
countries where companies producing vehicles have merged to become
big companies. If we cannot defend our industry, we will be
swallowed up by these big companies," Bernama news agency quoted
him as saying when asked to comment on his statement on Tuesday
calling for a second look at the AFTA's agreement to open up the
automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government needed to look after the automotive
industry as well as the interests of other companies which are
involved in the production of the national car.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his concern that if the agreement was implemented,
other industries involved in the manufacturing of the national car
could be exposed to the possibility of being shut down.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN countries decided earlier this year to defer the transfer
of completely built-up and completely knocked-down products of the
automotive industry from the Temporary Exclusion List to the
inclusion list on Jan 1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN Groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
