<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Urged to Avoid Marginalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries in the Asian
Pacific region must maximize the advantages and minimize the
negative effects of globalization, thus avoiding to be
marginalized, an senior official of the United Nations stressed
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the 56th commission session
of the U.N. Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the
Pacific (ESCAP) here, ESCAP Executive Secretary Adrianus Mooy said
developing countries' enhanced participation in the globalization
brings with certain risk.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian crisis amply demonstrated such participation is by
no means smooth nor does it guarantee equitable gains for all
countries and people," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged a regional perspective for developing countries on how
to manage globalization and seize new opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Besides the issue of globalization, the ESCAP session, being
held here from June 1 to 6, will focus on integrating developing
countries into the international trade system on a fair and
equitable basis.
</P>
<P>
Ministers and senior officials from 60 members and associate
member countries of the ESCAP attended Thursday's opening session.
</P>
<P>
Based in Bangkok, ESCAP is now the only region-wide forum in
the Asia-Pacific region which meets annually at the ministerial
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
