<HEADLINE> World Economic News Summary at 0445 GMT, June 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Sainsbury's, Britain's second biggest supermarket
group, has announced a steep drop in profits - blaming, in part,
the ongoing food price war.
</P>
<P>
Underlying pre-tax profits for the year to April 3 crashed 23
percent from 755 million pounds to 580 million pounds, although
sales rose 6.3 percent to 17.4 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
Sainsbury's said Wednesday that the profit plunge was due to a
poor performance by its core supermarket business caused by
vicious price-cutting measures and higher staff and property costs.
(UK-Price War)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuban sugar production amounts during the current
cycle to 4.058 million tons, increasing by seven percent over last
year, said Sugar Industry Ministry Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cuban sugar production dropped from 8.4 million tons in 1990 to
3.2 million tons in 1998, the lowest in history, with the arrival
of the economic crisis at the start of the last decade. (Cuba-
Sugar Output)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian bankruptcies fell sharply in April as the
country saw the continued trend of robust economic growth,
according to government statistics made available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were 6,715 cases of bankruptcy in April, a decline of 18.
1 percent from 8,201 recorded in March. The rate is also 8.9
percent lower than a year earlier, when the country registered a
total of 7,371 bankruptcies. (Canada-Bankruptcies Fall)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- A total of only 59,742 foreign tourists visited
Myanmar in the first two months of 2000, a 9.9 percent drop
compared with the same period of 1999 when 66,349 came, the
country's Central Statistical Organization said in its latest
report.
</P>
<P>
In the whole year of 1999, a total of 255,879 foreign tourists
visited Myanmar and the country's foreign exchange income earned
through tourism in the year was only over 30 million U.S. dollars.
(Myanmar-Tourism) 
</P>
</TEXT>
