<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Edges Knicks 88-79 in Eastern Conference Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Indiana Pacers overcame the
return of Patrick Ewing to edge the New York Knicks 88-79
Wednesday night in Indianapolis and take a 3-2 lead in the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers turned an 18-point deficit early in the second
quarter into a two-point lead by halftime, closing the period with
a 23-3 run.
</P>
<P>
Travis Best had his best game of the series with 24 points,
including 15 in the fourth quarter, while Jalen Rose scored 18
points and seven rebounds, Reggie Miller collected 16 points and
Mark Jackson added 11 points and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
Game 6 is Friday night at Madison Square Garden. In order to
win the series Knicks will still have to win a game at Indiana.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks will also have to find a way to score more points.
They had 32 in the first quarter in building their big lead, then
scored just eight in the second and 15 in the third.
</P>
<P>
Allan Houston led New York with 25 points. Ewing returned after
missing two games with foot tendinitis and had nine points and
four rebounds in the first quarter before
finishing with 13 points and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Larry Johnson, hampered by a foot injury sustained at the end
of Game 4, shot just 2-for-8 for four points, while Latrell
Sprewell was 4-for-14. The Knicks shot 12-for-19 in the first
quarter but 18-for-54 the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
Best shot 7-for-11 for the Pacers, who made 10 3-pointers, went
20-for-25 at the line and committed only seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
Indiana had 10 offensive rebounds to New York's three at
halftime, and Rose had 13 points. New York tied the game early in
the third quarter on a 3-pointer by Houston, but the Pacers scored
the next nine points and eventually went up by 11 as Jackson
backed his way into the lane and hit a jump hook. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
