<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Urged to Help Tackle Environment Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Environment Program (
UNEP) forum in Malmo, southern Sweden, issued a declaration on
Wednesday, urging the private sector and social organizations in
every country of the world to help cope with deteriorating
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
The three-day forum starting on Monday were attended by 600
specialists, including 80 environment ministers, representatives
of dozens of non-governmental organizations and leading
industrialists.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said that aside from the leading role the
government of each country is obliged to play, the private sector
and all social organizations and institutions should also shoulder
greater responsibilities in this respect to help turn the trend of
deterioration in the global environment.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the natural environment and resources on which
the mankind depends are getting worse at an astonishing speed
despite painstaking efforts made in protecting the world
environment by the international community since 1972, when the
United Nations called a meeting on mankind and environment in
Stockholm. A declaration was also issued at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
The forum attributed the worsening global environment to
various factors, including profound social and economic problems,
such as poverty, production, consumption as well as the unfairness
of wealth distribution and debt burdens.
</P>
<P>
The lack of international cooperation and impotence of actions
have also contributed to the deterioration, the document said.
</P>
<P>
To encourage the private sector to do more in environment
protection, the declaration called for the adoption of a "polluter
pays" principle, a system of environmental performance indicators
and reporting, and the establishment of a precautionary approach
in investment and technology decisions.
</P>
<P>
It urged social groups and institutions to play a part in
prompting policy-makers to put greater emphasis on green issues,
helping uplift the public awareness and renew the concept of
environment conservation, promoting transparency in environment
policy making to prevent corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
