<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Not to Tolerate Separatism: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will take
measures against the on-going Papua National Congress in Jayapura,
capital of Irian Jaya province, if it leads to efforts to separate
the area from Indonesia, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"If the discussions go too far and they, for instance, use the
meeting to declare Papua's independence, I think we (the
government) have to react," Antara News Agency Thursday quoted
Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Shihab did not say what kind of actions would be taken
by the government if the meeting declared Papua's independence.
</P>
<P>
The minister said President Abdurrahman Wahid would repudiate
the government's permission to hold the congress if its
discussions went out of line.
</P>
<P>
The president did not regard the congress as representative of
the people of Papua, meaning it had failed as a Papua National
Congress, Shihab noted.
</P>
<P>
President Wahid had said the congress, which started on May 29
and will end on June 3, was running "unnaturally" because it had
excluded Papuans opposed to separation from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the participants of the congress had unanimously
expressed their wishes that Papua should go out of the Republic of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Papua (Irian Jaya) is the largest island in Indonesia with a
population of about two million.
</P>
<P>
Besides representatives from 14 districts in the province, a
number of foreigners representing NGOs from several countries were
reportedly participating in the congress.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the congress' organizers said earlier, the
congress aimed to discuss the rectification of Papua's history,
review of its political status, legislation on protection of the
Papuan people, consolidation of the Papuan people's components and
basic rights of the Papuans.
</P>
<P>
President Wahid has refused to open the congress, but donated
125,000 U.S. dollars for its financing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
