<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Experiencing Heavy Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has been experiencing
heavy rains during the past two days, easing the prospects of an
impending power crisis.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rain accompanied by thunder and lightning lashed
Colombo and its suburbs inundating several roads and causing
traffic blocks Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Office workers and school children had to wade through flooded
roads and pelting rain to get to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological department here said that the long awaited
South-West Monsoon had set in and heavy showers with thunder and
lightening will be experienced during the next several weeks,
particularly in the Western region of the country.
</P>
<P>
The reservoirs in the catchment areas in the country have also
filled up, thereby easing the prospects of an impending power
crisis, the Daily News said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the Electricity Board announced an overall average
increase of 5.3 percent on electricity charges from Wednesday (
June 1).
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the cost of the supply of electricity will
increase by 10 percent in the domestic sector, by 3 percent in the
industrial sector and by 4 percent in the commercial sector.
</P>
<P>
The national Ceylon Electricity Board Friday appealed to the
public to conserve power in their daily activities as there is a
possibility of a power crisis in the country, if there is no
rainfall in the hydro catchment areas in the next two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
