<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Government Allots Land to Indigenous Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Ricardo Lagos
Wednesday announced 16 measures for the welfare of indigenous
Indian communities, including a development program allotting 50,
000 hectares of land to the Mapuche Indians by December 2001.
</P>
<P>
The government promises to respect the rights and culture of
the Indians and promote their development, Lagos said.
</P>
<P>
Under the measures, 10,000 Mapuche families will be granted 192
U.S. dollars each to buy seeds and other agricultural products
while the government will support the development of the land
plots and expand the Agriculture Ministry's technical assistance
programs.
</P>
<P>
The measures provide for an reinforcement of bilingual
education among the indigenous people, establishment of 10 family
health centers, as well as construction of roads, ports and
irrigation systems in the areas inhabited by the Mapuche Indians.
</P>
<P>
The Mapuche Indians in Chile have long been demanding what they
consider their ancestral lands, and some were engaged in violent
clashes against timber projects and a hydroelectric dam built 560
kilometers south of Santiago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
