<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Dental Check-up Program Launched in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Children in Beijing, Shanghai and
six other major cities in China will get free oral examinations
and dental consultations Friday and Saturday in public places such
as parks and squares.
</P>
<P>
The dental assistance is to celebrate the International
Children's Day and comes from the China Professional Oral Care
Center, reported the China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Health, based on the second
national oral health investigation conducted in 1995, indicate
that 76.55 percent of 5-year-olds in China have decayed teeth;
every child at that age average 4.48 rotten teeth.
</P>
<P>
The investigation also showed that 34.98 percent of 15-year-
olds have some diseased gums, the most serious among all age
groups.
</P>
<P>
The children-oriented activities mark the launch of a
nationwide program, 2000 China Oral Health Promotion, which seeks
to raise public awareness of the importance of dental care.
</P>
<P>
The program features three dental-health promotion vehicles
that will leave Shanghai on July 15 and tour 12 provinces and
municipalities using different routes before converging in Beijing
on September 20, National Day for Tooth Protection.
</P>
<P>
Free oral examinations and consultations will be offered that
day, while the work of the three traveling teams will be revealed
to the public.
</P>
<P>
Health ministry officials said the China Oral Health Promotion
program has reached nearly 4 million citizens in 14 provinces over
the past three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Drafts Plan for Dust Storm Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Science and
Technology has drafted a plan for prevention of dust storms and
desertification in China to be implemented in the following five
years.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Science and Technology said
the plan will be executed starting from 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, in the capital city of Beijing and
neighboring cities of Tianjin, Zhangjiakou and Chengde, more trees
and grass will be planted in both urban and suburban areas and
high-efficient agriculture will be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
In the capital's surrounding areas, vegetation coverage rate
will be increased and reclaimed farmland will be retired and
shifted to pastures.
</P>
<P>
In Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and the provinces of
Shaanxi, Liaoning, Hebei and Shanxi, where desertification is
accelerating, trees, shrub and grass will be planted to check the
trend.
</P>
<P>
Trees and grass will also be planted in retired farmland on the
hill slopes.
</P>
<P>
In overused and denuded grasslands, the major source of dust
storms that affect the capital and its surrounding areas, land
reclamation will be forbidden, crop farming will be stopped, and
pastures will be rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the fodder industry is to be encouraged for
the development of animal husbandry in the degraded pasture areas.
</P>
<P>
The plan also calls for more shelter forests to be planted.
</P>
<P>
For its smooth implementation, a number of experimental and
demonstration bases are to be built to promote the advanced and
effective techniques.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists will also strengthen basic research in
desertification prevention to improve the country's overall
capacity of fighting desertification.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0277 </DOCNO>
