<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Neal Unanimous Pick to All-NBA First Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- League Most Valuable Player
Shaquille O'Neal was a unanimous selection to the All-NBA First
Team, but the player he edged out for the scoring title -- Allen
Iverson -- had to settle for Second Team honours.
</P>
<P>
The superstar center of the Los Angeles Lakers became only the
fifth player since 1981-82 to be a unanimous choice for the All-
NBA First Team, joining Michael Jordan, Larry Bird, Karl Malone
and Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal fell one vote shy of becoming the first unanimous MVP in
league history earlier this month. That vote went to Philadelphia
76ers guard Iverson, who was denied a spot on the All-NBA First
Team.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal received the maximum 121 first-team votes and 605 points
from a panel of broadcasters and writers in the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Guard Gary Payton of the Seattle SuperSonics, who finished
sixth in the MVP voting, was second overall with 95 first-team
votes and 541 points.
</P>
<P>
Forwards Kevin Garnett of the Minnesota Timberwolves and Tim
Duncan of the San Antonio Spurs and guard Jason Kidd of the
Phoenix Suns joined O'Neal and Payton on the first team. Garnett,
the distant runner-up to O'Neal in the MVP voting, received 495
points followed by Duncan (460) and Kidd (445).
</P>
<P>
Iverson, a first-team All-NBA selection last season, received a
second-team high 420 points and 52 first-team votes.
</P>
<P>
Iverson is joined on the second team by Lakers guard Kobe
Bryant, center Alonzo Mourning of the Miami Heat and forwards
Malone of the Utah Jazz and Grant Hill of the Detroit Pistons.
</P>
<P>
The All-NBA Third Team consists of forwards Chris Webber of the
Sacramento Kings and Vince Carter of the Toronto Raptors, center
David Robinson of the Spurs and guards Stephon Marbury of the New
Jersey Nets and Eddie Jones of the Charlotte Hornets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
