<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Barak of Wasting Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat said here Thursday Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak is "wasting time" and should be held
responsible for the stalemate in the Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a meeting with European Union (EU)
Middle East special envoy Miguel Mauratinus. Early Thursday in the
Portuguese capital of Lisbon, Barak accused the Palestinians of "
foot-dragging" in the final-status peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"Barak's accusation is baseless because facts refute it. They
(the Israelis) are the party that procrastinates and wastes time to
evade the sincere implementation of the signed accords and Sharm el
Sheikh memo," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
"We have two letters of guarantee from the EU and the United
States for the memo that was signed under the auspices of Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and King Abdullah II of Jordan," he added,
referring to the Sharm el Sheikh memo signed last September.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he has no idea so far about when the talks with
Israel will be resumed. Earlier in the day, Arafat said no decision
has been made by the Palestinians on the resumption of the talks.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Mauratinus expressed the EU's interest in the
peace process and hoped that the peace talks will be resumed as
soon as possible. The EU is ready to help the Palestinian and
Israeli sides reach a framework agreement on the final-status
issues over the coming weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat's adviser Nabil Abu-Rudeina said Barak's
accusations "revealed the real intentions of the Israeli
government," which he said is not serious in the talks.
</P>
<P>
The coming week will be the final test of the Israeli
intentions, Abu-Rudeina added.
</P>
<P>
There have been two tracks of final-status talks. One was
attended by Israeli chief negotiator Oded Eran and his Palestinian
counterpart Yasser Abed Rabbo, while the other one was held between
Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and Palestinian
Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qurei.
</P>
<P>
But the back-channel talks were called off by Barak on May 21
due to an upsurge of violent anti-Israel demonstrations in the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has urged Clinton to put more pressure on Israel to force
it to make compromise in the final-status talks, which deal with
such thorny issues as Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, Jewish
settlements, border, security and water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baku-Ceyhan Pipeline Protocol Passes One Turkish Parliament Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish parliamentary Commission
for Industry approved on Thursday an intergovernmental agreement on
the construction of the Baku-Ceyhan Oil Pipeline between Turkey,
Azerbaijan and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which has been approved by the parliaments of
Azerbaijan and Georgia, will be subjected to ratification by the
Turkish parliamentary Commission for Foreign Affairs on Friday.
</P>
<P>
If the Foreign Affairs Commission votes for the agreement, the
issue will be debated in the full parliament to be legalized.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on transport of Caspian basin oil to world markets
was signed among the three countries under the promotion of U.S.
President Bill Clinton, on the sideline of Organization of Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) summit at Istanbul last November.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said the pipeline, starting from Azeri Caspian
port Baku to Turkish southern port city Ceyhan via Georgian capital
Tbilisi, is of political and strategic importance rather than a
lucrative investment.
</P>
<P>
They considered it a vital move of the U.S.-led western powers
to curb Russian and Iranian expansion of their influence in the
newly-independent Central Asia and Caucasus regions.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish parliament commission approved the agreement amid
Russian President Vladimir Putin's dramatic visits to Central Asian
countries, during which Russia and Turkmenistan signed a deal over
the sale of Turkmenian natural gas to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia is seen as Turkey's main competitor over the purchase of
Turkmen gas. Some Turkish experts argued that while Turkey lags
behind in its effort to secure access to gas and oil resources of
the Central Asia and Caucasus, Russia is trying to restore its
influences in the region.
</P>
<P>
Following its approval, the Turkish parliamentary commission
said that the Baku-Ceyhan project is very important for close ties
between countries in the region and the western world, which will
guarantee their prosperity and independence in the future.
</P>
<P>
"This project will increase Turkey's geostrategical importance
and help development of economic and social relations among the
regional countries," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, transportation of oil through this pipeline which has
one million barrel daily capacity via Ceyhan to the global market
will make Ceyhan an important international oil market center," the
commission added.
</P>
<P>
Cumhur Ersumer, energy and natural resources minister and deputy
prime minister, hailed the Baku-Ceyhan oil pipeline as another
expression of the Silk Road, adding it will make Turkey an energy
corridor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hostage Taker Shot, Injured But Hostages Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Police shot and severely injured
the gunman to run to the safe rescue of 25 children and their
three adult teachers Thursday, police sources confirmed.
</P>
<P>
A Luxembourg police sniper trained in on the 39-year-old
Tunisian-born immigrant before the police from Luxembourg and
neighboring Germany stormed the nursery school building to rescue
the hostages who had been kept captive for the past 28 hours.
</P>
<P>
The gunman, armed with a pistol, a hand grenade and a knife,
walked into the nursery school at Wasserbillig in eastern
Luxembourg and took almost 40 kids and their teachers hostage.
</P>
<P>
After speaking with his psychiatrist late Wednesday, the gunman
released 10 children. He had demanded to be flown to Libya
together with a ransom of 20 million francs (220,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The gunman released four more children Thursday before the
police decided to move in to the rescue of the children, aged
between 22 months and seven years.
</P>
<P>
Residents of the village heard shooting and saw police and
medical staff running to the nursery school building.
</P>
<P>
Officials later confirmed that all the hostages were safe and
sound and were only sent to a nearby hospital for physical checks
and for re-union with their parents.
</P>
<P>
The gunman was said to have a history of mental problems and
was a father of two. He and his wife along with their children
had been living near the nursery school for four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
