<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (RPT with Correction)Schroeder Holds Talks with Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder held talks with the visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Thursday evening in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
During the talks Schroeder expressed his concern that a
proposed U.S. National Missile Defense system could disrupt ties
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
After their talks Schroeder said at a news briefing with
Clinton: "We have to be careful that any such project does not
trigger the process of a renewed arms race."
</P>
<P>
Clinton presented his views on the NMD system"in a very frank
way", according to Schroeder. But Schroeder said : "I then stated
my concerns."
</P>
<P>
Schroeder and Clinton both stressed the importance of the
partnership with Russia: "The world and especially Europe needs an
intact relationships with Russia." Two leaders expressed their
supports for the Russian President Vladimir Putin and backed the
political and economic stability in Russia.
</P>
<P>
After ending his visit to Portugal and attending the summit
conference of the E.U. and the United States in Lisbon, Clinton
arrived in Berlin on Thursday to make his three-day visit to
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will travel to Aachen, a small city on the border to
Belgium, to receive the Charlemagne Prize of this year. Then he
returns to Berlin to take part in the "Third Way" summit
conference in which altogether 13 heads of state and government
will attend.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will travel to Moscow this weekend and talk with the
Russian Federal President Vladimir Putin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rebound Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks bounced back
again Thursday amid more signs of slower U.S. economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Industrial average closed up 129.87 or 1.24
percent at 10,652.20. The blue chip index fell 4.8 points
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 181.59 or 5.3
percent at 3,582.50. The composite rose 254.37 points Tuesday but
fell 58.57 points Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 28.21 at 1,448.81.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied as three separate reports showed the U.S.
economic growth slowed a bit and therefore investors moved into
the tech and industrial sectors to buy.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Purchasing Managers said its index
of manufacturing activity fell 1.7 points to 53.2 percent while
the Commerce Department reported construction spending fell 0.6
percent in April, the biggest decline in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
In the retail sector, sales were weak in May due to higher
consumer credit costs after the Federal Reserve had raised
interest rates six times since last June in an effort to cool off
the economy and keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in the economy suggested that the Federal
tightening is working. Wall Street analysts believed the
tightening cycle is nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch, the global securities research &AMP; economics group,
said in the latest survey that The Federal Reserve is expected to
tighten once or, at most, two more times in 25 basis point
increments. The group doubted that the Federal Reserve would need
to go beyond that, because the economy already appears to be
moderating.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 7.86 at 651.46 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 7.48 at 912.45. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 16.29 at 492.47.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,066 up, 925 down and 412
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased slightly to 951.18 million shares from
950.36 million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000601.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Holds Talks with Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder held talks with the visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Friday evening in Berlin.
</P>
