<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International HIV/AIDS Conference Opens in Toronto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced 120 million
Canadian dollars (about 80 million U.S. dollars) in contribution
to fight AIDS in developing countries at an international
conference opened in Toronto Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Maria Minna, Canadian Minister for International Cooperation,
who hosts the two-day international conference on HIV/AIDS, said
the funding will be provided through the Canadian International
Development Agency (CIDA) over three years.
</P>
<P>
"Today's contribution is part of an aggressive Canadian plan to
fight HIV/AIDS around the world, which is one of the single
biggest threats to development," she said.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Minna also unveiled an Action Plan to
control and prevent the spread of the disease in developing
countries and countries in transition.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, CIDA will ensure at least 95 percent of young
men and women aged 15-24 in some developing countries have access
to the information, education to reduce their vulnerability to HIV
infection.
</P>
<P>
One of the major projects will be in Africa, where CIDA will
provide 13 million Canadian dollars (about 8.7 million U.S.
dollars)to focus on the behavioural change needed to prevent the
spread of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 20 countries are attending the
HIV/AIDS conference, the first of its kind ever held in this
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
