<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Market for 3G Wireless Services to Explode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Revenue for U.S. wireless third
generation (3G) operators is expected to grow more than 71 percent
annually in the next five years, according to a new study released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. wireless operator revenue will jump from 4.3 billion U.S.
dollars in 2002 to 63 billion dollars while wireless
infrastructure purchases will grow more than 53 percent annually
from 4 billion dollars to 34 billion dollars during the same five-
year period.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by the Phillips Group, a global
research and consulting firm focused on the telecommunications and
IT industries.
</P>
<P>
Introduced in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the first
generation (1G) of mobile cellular communications systems were
analog, primarily used for voice. Starting in the 1990s, second
generation (2G) systems used digital encoding and have been used
mostly for voice. 3G systems apply high-speed data transfer and
state-of-the-art terminal technology enabling wireless multimedia
service. Its goals include high-quality audio and video and
advanced roaming. In addition, for those companies involved, 3G is
their opportunity to build the wireless Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
