<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Urges To Deepen Trade Ties with Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chighizola said that during the last decade trade relations
between Argentina and Mexico were meager, specially after Mexico's
incorporation into North America Free Trade Area (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
Trade between Argentina and Mexico fell 16.8 percent in the
1999 January-October period, compared with 1998's same period,
according to figures of Argentina-Mexico Trading Chamber.
</P>
<P>
During January-October 1999, Mexico's exports were 363.4
million U.S. dollars, while Argentina's reached 136.4 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Those present at the meeting agreed to promote trade relations
between both countries and expressed hope that Mexico becomes a
bridge between the United States and Argentina for the Southern
Comon Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
NAFTA is composed by Canada, the United States and Mexico,
while Mercosur includes Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Bolivia and Chile as associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
